{"title_page": "Wawa (company)", "text_new": "{{short description|American convenience store chain}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Wawa, Inc.\n| logo             = [[File:Wawa logo.svg|200px]]\n| type             = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| founder          = Grahame Wood\n| location_city    = [[Wawa, Pennsylvania|Wawa]], [[Pennsylvania]]\n| location_country = United States<ref name=\"Forbes2017\"/>\n| area_served      = [[Mid-Atlantic states]], [[Florida]]\n| locations        = 842 stores (2019)<ref name=\"csnews.com\">{{cite web|url=https://csnews.com/top-100-convenience-store-chains-2019|title=Wawa Inc.|publisher=}}</ref><ref>http://csnews.com/wawa-test-smaller-c-store-format-philadelphia retrieved August 3, 2019</ref>\n| key_people       = [[Chris Gheysens]] ([[Chief Executive Officer|CEO]])<ref name=\"BestMet\">{{cite web|url=http://best-met.com/news/wawa-ceo-howard-stoeckel-retired-2012/ |title=Wawa CEO Howard Stoeckel To Retire At The End Of 2012 &#124; Food World &#124; Food Trade News |publisher=Best-met.com |date= |accessdate=2018-02-09}}</ref>\n| industry         = {{unbulleted list|[[Convenience store]]|[[Gas station]]|[[Fast food]]}}\n| products         = {{unbulleted list|Coffee|[[Submarine sandwich|Hoagies]]|Prepared foods|Gasoline|Beverages|Snacks|Dairy products|Salads}}\n| revenue          = {{profit}} [[US$]]10.6&nbsp;billion (2017)<ref name=\"Forbes2017\">{{cite web | url=https://www.forbes.com/companies/wawa/ | title=Wawa on the Forbes America's Best Employers 2019 List | publisher=Forbes | accessdate=May 18, 2019}}</ref>\n| net_income       = {{increase}} US$118 million (2011)<ref name=forbes>{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2011/21/private-companies-11_Wawa_ZHC5.html |title=#47 Wawa |year=2012 |work=[[Forbes]]}}</ref>\n| assets           = {{increase}} US$1.57 billion (2011)<ref name=forbes/>\n| num_employees    = 31,000 (2017)<ref name=\"Forbes2017\"/>\n| parent           = Wild Goose Holding Co.\n| homepage         = {{URL|www.wawa.com}}\n| logo_caption     = \n| image            = Wawa station in Montgomery County, Pennsylvania.jpg\n| image_caption    = Wawa gas station in [[Skippack, Pennsylvania]]\n| foundation       = {{Start date and age|1964|04|16}}\n}}\n\n'''Wawa, Inc.''' ({{IPAc-en|w|\u0251\u02d0|w|\u0251\u02d0}} {{respell|WAH-WAH}}) is an American chain of [[convenience store]]s and [[gas station]]s located along the [[East Coast of the United States]], operating in [[Pennsylvania]], [[New Jersey]], [[Delaware]], [[Maryland]], [[Virginia]], [[Washington, D.C.]], and [[Florida]].<ref name=\"AboutWawa\">{{cite web | url=https://www.wawa.com/About.aspx#aboutwawa | title=About Wawa | publisher=Wawa | date=2016 | accessdate=May 9, 2016}}</ref> The company's corporate headquarters is located in the [[Wawa, Pennsylvania|Wawa]] area of [[Chester Heights, Pennsylvania]] in [[Greater Philadelphia]].<!--Cited below--> {{As of|2008}}, Wawa was the largest convenience store chain in Greater Philadelphia, and it is also the third-largest retailer of food in Greater Philadelphia, after [[Acme Markets]] and [[ShopRite (United States)|ShopRite]].<ref name=\"Inquirer\">\"[http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=PI&s_site=philly&p_multi=PI&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F53D038D91AB567&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM Wawa's wonders of retailing,  The dairy and convenience-store chain is marking 100 years.]\" ''[[Philadelphia Inquirer]]''. August 5, 2002. D01. Retrieved on December 21, 2011. \"Wawa not only dominates the convenience-store business in the Philadelphia region but is also the third-largest food retailer, trailing only Acme Markets and ShopRite.\" and \"To boost sales, the company opened its first Wawa Food Market in 1964 in Folsom, Delaware County. Stores now spread from central Pennsylvania and central New Jersey to southern Virginia. In the 1970s, the company began selling more coffee by the cup,[...]\"</ref><ref name=\"Wood\">{{cite news|last=Wood|first=Anthony R.|title=A little dairy with a big idea How success came to Wawa|publisher=[[Philadelphia Inquirer]]|date=April 16, 2009|url=http://articles.philly.com/2009-04-16/news/25287891_1_wawa-coffee-sellers-professor-of-food-marketing|accessdate=December 21, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:WAWA.gif|thumb|left|Old Wawa logo used from 1990 to 2004. This logo is still in use at many locations.]]\nThe Wawa business began in 1803 as an iron [[foundry]].<ref name=\"AboutWawa\"/> In 1890, George Wood, an entrepreneur from [[New Jersey]],<ref name=\"Wawaplace3\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.philly.com/1989-06-15/news/26107992_1_franklin-mint-wawa-road-post-office/3 |title=Pay A Visit To Wawa, The Place |publisher=[[Philadelphia Inquirer]] |date=June 15, 1989|author=Mayer, Cynthia|accessdate=2018-12-09|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303234716/http://articles.philly.com/1989-06-15/news/26107992_1_franklin-mint-wawa-road-post-office|archive-date=March 3, 2016}}</ref> moved to [[Delaware County, Pennsylvania]]; it was here that he began the Wawa Dairy Farm.<ref name=\"Wawaplace3\"/> Wood imported [[Guernsey cattle|cows]] from the [[Crown dependencies|British Crown dependency]] island of [[Guernsey]], and bought {{convert|1000|acre|ha}} of land in the [[Chester Heights]] area;<ref name=\"Wawaplace3\"/> the corporate headquarters would later be renamed [[Wawa, Pennsylvania|Wawa]]. Since [[pasteurization]] was not yet available, many children faced sickness from consuming [[raw milk]]. Wood arranged for doctors to certify his milk was sanitary and safe for consumption, which convinced many consumers to buy the product.<ref name=\"Wawaplace3\"/> The strategy worked, and allowed the Wawa dairy to grow. Demand for dairy products grew rapidly during the 1920s, and so did the company. Wawa began using the slogan \"Buy Health by the Bottle\"; they served customers in Pennsylvania and New Jersey, delivering milk to customers' homes.\n\nIn the 1960s, however, many consumers began buying milk in stores instead of using home delivery. Wawa started to open its own stores to adjust to these market changes.<ref name=\"AboutWawa\"/><ref name=\"Wawaplace3\"/> On April 16, 1964, Grahame Wood, George Wood's grandson, opened the first Wawa Food Market at 1212 MacDade Boulevard in [[Folsom, Pennsylvania]],<ref name=\"WawaTimeline\"/> which remained in operation until June 17, 2016, when it closed in favor of a new \"Super Wawa\" down the street. A parade was held from the original location to the new store on opening day.<ref name=\"Wood\"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Ormsby|first=Barbara|title=Wawa closing its original store|work=[[Daily Local News]]|location=West Chester, PA|date=July 21, 2014|url=http://www.dailylocal.com/general-news/20140721/wawa-closing-its-original-store|accessdate=July 21, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"1StoreClose\">{{cite web |url=http://www.philly.com/philly/blogs/real-time/Wawas-1st-store-closes.html |title=Wawa's 1st store closes today |last=Babay |first=Emily |date=June 17, 2016 |website=Philly.com |publisher=Philadelphia Media Network |accessdate=January 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Wawa Food Market stores were also part of a then-new trend in retailing, the [[convenience store]]. Open both earlier and later than traditional [[supermarket]]s, they carried other foods and beverages besides milk, as well as other items from the Wawa dairy.\n[[File:Wawa Dairy Farms.JPG|thumb|The old Wawa Dairy Farms building in [[Wawa, Pennsylvania]]]]\n\nIn 1977, Wawa began sharing ownership of the company with its associates through [[profit-sharing]] plans. In 1992, Wawa formalized its associate ownership with its [[Employee Stock Ownership Plan]] (ESOP), with stock being awarded to associates annually based on the prior year's service. Because the company is privately held, Wawa secures an independent assessment of its stock value at regular intervals to ensure that the ESOP is fairly maintained.  Today, the ESOP accounts for more than 40% of Wawa stock.\n\n==Company==\n\n===Name and logo===\nThe [[store chain|chain]]'s name comes from the site of the company's first milk plant and corporate headquarters in the [[Wawa, Pennsylvania]] area. The name of the town ''Wawa'' is in turn derived from the [[Ojibwe]] word for the [[Canada goose]] (taken from ''[[The Song of Hiawatha]]'').{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} An image of a goose in flight serves as the Wawa [[corporate logo]]. It is said that the goose was chosen because the company employs the principles of teamwork, group consensus, and encouragement. It is also rumored that the origin of the name stems from the sound a goose makes.\n\n===Leadership===\nThe current CEO of Wawa is [[Chris Gheysens]], who succeeded Howard Stoeckel in January 2013.<ref name=\"BestMet\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://people.forbes.com/profile/howard-b-stoeckel/5363 |title=Howard B. Stoeckel Profile |accessdate=October 16, 2008 | work=Forbes}}</ref> [[Du Pont family|Eleuth\u00e8re (Th\u00e8re) du Pont]] has served as both the CFO and president, but is no longer associated with the company. Richard D. (Dick) Wood, Jr. is chairman of the [[board of directors]].  Many Wood family members are active in the company. Although Wawa is a [[family business|family-run business]], Wawa associates own roughly 50% of the company, more than 40% of which is owned through the company's employee stock-ownership program.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://getpocket.com/explore/item/the-inside-story-of-wawa-the-beloved-10-billion-convenience-store-chain-taking-over-the-east-coast|title=The Inside Story of Wawa, the Beloved $10 Billion Convenience Store Chain Taking Over the East Coast|accessdate=October 11, 2019| work=Inc}}</ref>\n\n===Holdings and locations===\n[[File:Wawa gas station Willow Grove PA.jpeg|thumb|right|A typical Wawa convenience store and gas station in [[Willow Grove, Pennsylvania]]]]\nIn 2015, Wawa ranked 34th on the ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine list of the largest [[private company|private companies]], with total revenues of $9.68 billion.<ref name=\"Forbes2015\">{{cite web | url=https://www.forbes.com/companies/wawa/ | title=Wawa on the Forbes America's Largest Private Companies List | publisher=Forbes | accessdate=March 27, 2016}}</ref> {{As of|2016}}, Wawa employs over 22,000 people<ref name=\"AboutWawa\"/><ref name=\"Forbes2015\"/> in 720+ stores (450+ offering gasoline).<ref name=\"WawaXfinity\">{{cite web | url=https://www.wawa.com/pdfs/042616_Comcast%20Wawa%20WiFi%20Press%20Release_FINAL.pdf | title=Wawa and Comcast team up to deliver free wi-fi at more than 700 East Coast locations | publisher=Wawa | date=April 26, 2016 | accessdate=May 9, 2016}}</ref> {{As of|2008}}, Wawa's New Jersey stores were concentrated mostly in [[South Jersey]].<!--Stick strictly to what the references say, please!--><ref>Strauss, Robert. \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/13/nyregion/nyregionspecial2/13movienj.html North Jersey or South? A Search for the Line].\" ''[[The New York Times]]''. July 13, 2008. Retrieved on December 23, 2011. \"There is the 'hoagie-sub' question: 'Hoagie' is a South Jersey term for a sandwich on a long roll, while a sub is the North Jersey version. No self-respecting North Jersey resident would know the Philadelphia Eagles fight song, and no South Jersey fan would wear a Giants T-shirt. Wawa stores dot the South, while North Jersey folks get their caffeine at a 7-11.\"</ref>\n\n{{As of|1989}} Wawa Inc. <!--\"Dated\" material should be kept-->and the Wood family together control about {{convert|725|acre|ha}} of land, containing the corporate headquarters, the Wawa dairy farm, and J.T. Farms, within two municipalities in [[Delaware County, Pennsylvania]]. The properties are located in [[Chester Heights, Pennsylvania|Chester Heights]] and [[Middletown Township, Delaware County, Pennsylvania|Middletown Township]]. Wawa Inc. owns {{convert|50|acre|ha}} of land around \"Red Roof,\" the corporate headquarters, {{convert|150|acre|ha}} of land around the Wawa dairy, and the {{convert|225|acre|ha|adj=on}} J.T. Farms. The Wood family owns {{convert|300|acre|ha}} of estate property. Cynthia Mayer of the ''[[Philadelphia Inquirer]]'' said that, as a result of the land holdings, the Wood family was \"the closest thing to a feudal barony this side of du Pont.\"<ref name=\"Wawaplace3\"/>\n\nBeginning in the 1940s, the dairy facility began selling excess parcels of land. In 1964, it sold about 40 acres to the [[Franklin Mint]]. Several years prior to 1989, the dairy sold 25 acres of land to a retirement complex, Granite Farms Estates. The process of selling excess land continued sporadically.\n\nWawa Inc. owns the 225-acre J.T. Farms, a separate farm property. {{As of|1989}} Wawa Inc. leases it to Bill Faul, who maintained a herd of 100 Holstein cattle and paid $1,500 (currently $2778.12) per month. Wawa continued to own the farm due to symbolic reasons. It also kept heifers along Route 1 in a strip of land adjacent to the plant which did not produce milk; Fritz Schroeder, then-vice president of Wawa Inc., said in 1989, \"[w]e like them for the ambiance.\"<ref name=\"Wawaplace4\">Mayer, Cynthia. \"Pay A Visit To Wawa, The Place.\" ''[[Philadelphia Inquirer]]''. June 15, 1989. D4. p. [http://articles.philly.com/1989-06-15/news/26107992_1_franklin-mint-wawa-road-post-office/4 4]. Retrieved on September 16, 2012.</ref>\n\nWawa, for the most part, covers parts of Pennsylvania not already served by fast-growing rival stores [[Sheetz]], [[Rutter's]], and [[Turkey Hill Minit Markets|Turkey Hill]]. Wawa is often compared to Sheetz due to their similar business models and Pennsylvania roots.<ref name=\"Sheetz\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.philly.com/2013-04-01/business/38165625_1_lou-sheetz-dairy-farm-coffee-business |title=Archives - Philly.com |publisher=Articles.philly.com |date= |accessdate=2018-02-09}}</ref>\n\n====Corporate headquarters====\n[[File:Wawa Red Roof.JPG|thumb|\"Red Roof\" at Wawa headquarters in [[Chester Heights, Pennsylvania]]]]\nThe company's corporate headquarters is located in the [[Wawa, Pennsylvania|Wawa]] area, along [[Baltimore Pike]]<ref name=\"Wawaplace1\">Mayer, Cynthia. \"Pay A Visit To Wawa, The Place.\" ''[[Philadelphia Inquirer]]''. June 15, 1989. D4. p. [http://articles.philly.com/1989-06-15/news/26107992_1_franklin-mint-wawa-road-post-office 1]. Retrieved on September 16, 2012.</ref><ref>\"[http://www.wawa.com/WawaWeb/About.aspx About Wawa] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140317200208/http://www.wawa.com/WawaWeb/About.aspx |date=March 17, 2014 }}.\" Wawa Inc. Retrieved on February 18, 2011. \"Headquarters Red Roof, Baltimore Pike Wawa, Pennsylvania 19063.\"</ref> in [[Chester Heights, Pennsylvania|Chester Heights]].<ref name=Starkoptions>Stark, Kenn. \"[http://delcotimes.com/articles/2011/12/05/news/doc4edd3e6cc214b403007473.txt Chester Heights mulls options in light of proposed tax hike].\" ''[[Delaware County Daily Times]]''. Monday December 5, 2011. Retrieved on September 16, 2012. \"Currently, about 300 Wawa employees work at the Red Roof corporate headquarters in Chester Heights.\"</ref><ref>\"[http://www.chesterheights.org/Zoning%20Map.html Borough of Chester Heights Zoning Map].\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6Aj5rtdLf?url=http://www.chesterheights.org/Zoning-Page.jpg Archive]) [[Borough of Chester Heights]]. Retrieved on September 16, 2012.</ref> The headquarters is in proximity to [[Middletown Township, Delaware County, Pennsylvania|Middletown Township]].<ref name=\"NYTBan\">\"[https://www.nytimes.com/1999/05/09/us/stores-post-billboard-ads-for-tobacco-despite-ban.html Stores Post Billboard Ads for Tobacco, Despite Ban].\" ''[[The New York Times]]''. May 9, 1999. Retrieved on December 23, 2011.</ref> {{As of|2011}} about 300 employees work in the headquarters. The Borough of Chester Heights receives a majority of its local services tax from employees of Wawa.<ref name=Starkoptions/>\n\n==Programs and promotions==\nWawa provides surcharge-free ATMs, the result of a partnership with [[PNC Bank]] that began in 1985. Wawa implemented the program in stores in 1996. In 2010, Wawa surpassed 1 billion transactions under the PNC brand.<ref name=\"ATMMarketplace\">{{cite web | url=http://www.atmmarketplace.com/article/127662/Wawa-hits-1-billion-ATM-transactions-with-PNC-brand | title=Wawa hits 1 billion ATM transactions with PNC brand | publisher=Networld Media Group | work=ATM Marketplace | date=April 19, 2010 | accessdate=May 9, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201170357/http://www.atmmarketplace.com/article/127662/Wawa-hits-1-billion-ATM-transactions-with-PNC-brand |archive-date=February 1, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the late 1980s and through the 1990s, Wawa engaged in a scholarship sponsorship program that involved Irish students (mainly from [[University College Cork|UCC]] in Cork, Ireland) running some stores on the Pennsylvania Main Line, allowing the students to study for their MBAs from Saint Joseph's University in Philadelphia.<ref name=\"SJUScholarship\">{{cite web | url=http://www.sju.edu/ucomm/archives/2003/december/hawkeye_12082003.html | title=Scholarship Program Links SJU and Northern Ireland | publisher=[[Saint Joseph's University]] | work=HawkEye | date=December 8, 2003 | accessdate=May 9, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927003905/http://www.sju.edu/ucomm/archives/2003/december/hawkeye_12082003.html |archive-date=September 27, 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Wawa coffee bar.jpg|thumb|left|upright|A Wawa coffee bar counter with different flavors. A staple of Wawa stores for years, the glass carafes were replaced with coffee dispensers around 2010.]]\n\nIn 1994, Wawa opened a store in [[Center City, Philadelphia]], which sold food only.<ref name=\"Westfeldt\">Westfeldt, Amy. \"[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=O5c_AAAAIBAJ&sjid=CFYMAAAAIBAJ&pg=5174,5376452&dq=wawa+pennsylvania+institution&hl=en Convenience Stores in the '90s].\" ''[[Associated Press]]'' at the ''[[Warsaw Times-Union]]''. Saturday July 27, 1996. 10C. Retrieved from [[Google News]] (14/39) on January 1, 2011.</ref>\n\nIn 1994, Wawa debuted the \"Super Wawa\", larger stores with public restrooms and more parking. Gasoline pumps were added in 1996.<ref name=\"BCTWawa\">{{cite news | url=http://www.burlingtoncountytimes.com/business/wawa-history-through-the-years/article_b4abed32-c050-51f0-bd29-ee3711d8d1aa.html | title=Wawa history through the years | work=[[Burlington County Times]] | date=April 16, 2014 | accessdate=May 9, 2016 | author=Bishop, Chris}}</ref><ref name=\"WawaTimeline\">{{cite web | url=https://www.wawa.com/wawatimeline.aspx | title=Wawa Timeline | publisher=Wawa | date=2014 | accessdate=May 9, 2016}}</ref> On October 21, 2010, Wawa began testing the sale of [[diesel fuel]] at 12 of its New Jersey locations due to an increasing number of cars using this fuel.<ref name=\"CSPNews\">{{cite web | url=http://www.cspnet.com/ME2/Audiences/dirmod.asp?sid=&nm=&type=Publishing&mod=Publications::Article&mid=8F3A7027421841978F18BE895F87F791&AudID=CBA745B91AFB44FA923476ACBBD040A5&tier=4&id=E6DDDEBA76D9433B9D01DFF2677E37CB | title=Wawa Mulling Diesel Deal | publisher=CSP Daily News | date=October 22, 2010 | accessdate=May 9, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708212809/http://www.cspnet.com/ME2/Audiences/dirmod.asp?sid=&nm=&type=Publishing&mod=Publications::Article&mid=8F3A7027421841978F18BE895F87F791&AudID=CBA745B91AFB44FA923476ACBBD040A5&tier=4&id=E6DDDEBA76D9433B9D01DFF2677E37CB | archive-date=July 8, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2000s, Wawa was among the first stores to implement [[self-serve]] computer [[touch-screen]] menus for food orders, in an attempt to improve order accuracy, speed and for upselling.<ref name=\"Screen\">{{cite web | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/goingoutguide/why-you-may-soon-be-ordering-lunch-on-a-touch-screen-kiosk/2017/03/01/0b964a90-f915-11e6-bf01-d47f8cf9b643_story.html|title= Why touch screens are changing how we order at restaurants |date=March 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Wawa and [[McLane Company#Customers|McLane Co.]] reached a 30-year agreement to construct a distribution center in [[Carney's Point, New Jersey]], to handle the majority of Wawa's distribution.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foodlogistics.com/article/10255783/golden-pallet-award |title=Golden Pallet Award - A Unique Partnership That Delivers |author=Katherine Doherty |date=September 9, 2009|work= |publisher=Food Logistics |accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"McLaneWhitePaper\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mclaneco.com/www/AnonDocs/Solutions/ThirdParty/WAWA_whitepaper.pdf |title=Business Case: Third-Party Supply Chain Solutions |author=McLane Company |date=April 2009 |publisher=McLane Company |accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref> The center began operation in May 2004.<ref name=\"McLaneWhitePaper\"/>\n\nIn 2005, Wawa partnered with JPMorgan Chase to offer a Visa credit card branded with the Wawa name. It ceased issuing new cards in December 2007 and the program was canceled in November 2010.<ref>\"[http://www.philly.com/philly/blogs/inq-phillydeals/Bank_cancels_Wawas_credit_cards.html Wawa's credit cards canceled].\" ''[[Philadelphia Inquirer]]''. October 14, 2010. Retrieved on November 24, 2010.</ref> Wawa would later partner with Citi to restart the Wawa credit card program.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wawa.com/wawacreditcard/ |title=Credit Card: Save on Fuel with the Wawa Gas Credit Card |publisher=Wawa |date= |accessdate=2018-02-09}}</ref>\n\nWawa moved into social media to connect with its customers, and in 2006, its \"I Love Wawa\" MySpace page had over 5,000 members. By the middle of 2013, its Facebook page had reached nearly 1.1 million likes.<ref>Walker, Rob. \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/07/30/magazine/30wwln_consumed.html Convenience Cult?]\" ''[[The New York Times]]''. July 30, 2006. Retrieved on December 23, 2011.</ref>\n\nOn June 30, 2010, 20 Wawa locations in Pennsylvania started a trial of selling [[Pennsylvania Lottery]] tickets from automated kiosks. On December 6, 2010, it announced that all 210 Pennsylvania Wawa locations would sell lottery tickets from kiosks by spring 2011.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.csnews.com/tmp-financial/wawa-expands-pennsylvania-lottery-program | title=Wawa Expands Pennsylvania Lottery Program | publisher=Stagnito Media | work=ConvenienceStoreNews | date=December 6, 2010 | accessdate=April 15, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nbcphiladelphia.com/news/politics/Wawas-Across-PA-Get-Lottery-Kiosks-111407039.html | title=Wawa Bets on Pa. Lottery | publisher=[[NBCUniversal]] | work=[[WCAU|NBC 10]] | date=December 6, 2010 | accessdate=April 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn April 16, 2014, to celebrate its 50th anniversary, Wawa gave away free coffee and launched a nonprofit foundation to donate $50 million to health and hunger initiatives.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcall.com/news/breaking/mc-wawa-anniversary-free-coffee-20140416,0,3265420.story |title= Free coffee at Wawa to mark 50th anniversary |publisher=[[The Morning Call]]|date=April 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Products==\nWawa offers products found at most convenience chain marts such as chips, drinks, and soda. Wawa also sells its own branded iced tea, orange juice, and milk. Wawa used to sell its own branded soda but it has been discontinued. Wawa has [[Coca-Cola Freestyle]] soda fountains.\n\nKey products include its variety of coffee, latte, and cappuccino flavors and sizes, and made-to-order [[hoagies]]. Wawa also offers a brand of hot breakfast products, most famous of which is the \"Sizzli\", and also a full [[Delicatessen|deli]] with touch-screen ordering of sandwiches, hot sides, drinks, and deli meats. Wawa sells alcohol in Florida, Virginia, and at one Pennsylvania location in [[Chadds Ford, Pennsylvania|Chadds Ford]].<ref name=\"DelCoTimesBeer\">{{cite news | url=http://www.delcotimes.com/article/DC/20150614/NEWS/150619814 | title=Wawa hops into the beer-sales market | work=[[Delaware County Daily Times]] | date=June 14, 2015 | accessdate=May 9, 2016 | author=Logue, Tim}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Wilson|first=Shawnette|title=Chadds Ford Wawa Soon To Sell Beer|publisher=WTXF-TV|location=Philadelphia, PA|date=August 4, 2015|url=http://www.fox29.com/news/chadds-ford-wawa-soon-to-sell-beer#/|accessdate=January 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFor a short time between 1994 and 1996, Wawa sold [[Pizza Hut]] Personal Pan Pizzas and [[Taco Bell]] burritos.<ref name=\"Westfeldt\"/>\n\nIn 2018, Wawa introduced a [[secret menu]] to celebrate its 54th anniversary. It can be accessed by tapping the flapping goose in the bottom left corner of the ordering screen. As of June 2018, it contains a Birthday Cake Smoothie, a Birthday Cake Milkshake, and a Mac & Cheese Cheesesteak.\n\n==Store locations==\n[[File:Wawa footprint 2019-12.png|thumb|Wawa footprint as of December 2019]]\nWawa operates stores in [[Delaware]], [[Florida]], [[Maryland]], [[South Jersey|Southern New Jersey]], [[Pennsylvania]], [[Virginia]], and [[Washington, D.C.]] Wawa's territory once stretched into [[North Jersey|Northern New Jersey]], [[New York (state)|New York]] and [[Connecticut]], but in the late 1990s, the decision was made to abandon the franchised stores in the [[New York metropolitan area]] and [[New England]], as it was too competitive. The abandoned stores were re-branded when they were sold to Krauszer's (in Connecticut) and a variety of other convenience retailers, but most are still recognizable as they retain their distinctive \"Wawa\" design. The company continued to operate numerous stores in [[Central Jersey]] and South Jersey, and re-entered North Jersey in 2010, when Wawa opened a new store in [[Parsippany, New Jersey|Parsippany]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Paik|first=Eugene|url=http://www.nj.com/news/local/index.ssf/2010/06/wawas_parsippany_store_will_be.html|title=Wawa's Parsippany store will be its northern-most location|publisher=[[The Star-Ledger]]|date=June 14, 2010|accessdate=December 16, 2010}}</ref> Wawa opened its 100th Super Wawa in New Jersey on October 12, 2012, in [[Woodbridge, New Jersey|Woodbridge]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Bell|first=Deborah|url=http://woodbridge.patch.com/articles/wawa-set-to-open-in-ford-on-friday|title=Wawa Set to Open New Fords Store This Friday|work=Woodbridge Patch|date=October 9, 2012|accessdate=December 21, 2012}}</ref> Wawa moved farther into North Jersey opening in [[Kearny, New Jersey|Kearny]] on January 11, 2013, and [[Lodi, New Jersey|Lodi]] on October 4, 2013. The company plans to open five Wawas a year in North Jersey for the next 10 to 12 years.<ref>{{cite news|last=Genovese|first=Peter|url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2013/01/wawa_in_mahwah_some_day_chain.html|title=Wawa in Mahwah some day? Chain invades North Jersey |work=[[The Star-Ledger]]|date=January 11, 2013|accessdate=January 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn July 18, 2012, Wawa entered the Florida market when it opened its first location in [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cfnews13.com/content/news/cfnews13/news/article.html/content/news/articles/cfn/2012/7/18/florida_s_first_wawa.html|title=Florida's first Wawa opens today in Orlando, Orlando|work=Central Florida News 13|date=July 18, 2012}}</ref> It had expanded to more than 70 Florida locations by the end of 2015, with plans for 120 more by 2022.<ref name=\"SSWawa\">{{cite web | url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/business/consumer/fl-wawa-south-florida-plans-20151109-story.html | title=Wawa plans 120 stores in South Florida | work=[[Sun Sentinel]] | date=November 9, 2015 | accessdate=July 1, 2016 | author=Valverde, Miriam}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2018|05}}, Wawa has over 800 locations across Delaware, Maryland, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Virginia, and Florida.<ref name=\"csnews.com\"/>\n\nIn some [[Jersey Shore]] towns, Wawa designs its stores to match the aesthetic, and changes operating procedures to adapt to shore culture. In [[Cape May, New Jersey|Cape May]], Wawa has a Victorian-themed store. In [[Wildwood, New Jersey|Wildwood]], there is a 1950s-themed store.<ref name=\"Warner1\">{{cite news|last=Warner|first=Susan|title=Mom and Pop Hold Sway At the Shore|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=August 14, 2005|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/14/nyregion/nyregionspecial2/14njCHAINS.html?pagewanted=all |accessdate=December 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\nWawa opened its largest location at the time in the [[Farragut Square]] area of Washington, D.C. on December 14, 2017.<ref>{{cite news|last=Aggarwal|first=Nehal|url=https://www.washingtonian.com/2017/12/14/dcs-first-wawa-opens-with-selfie-screens-and-nitro-coffee/|title=DC\u2019s First Wawa Opens With Selfie-Screens and Nitro Coffee|work=[[Washingtonian (magazine)|Washingtonian]]|date=December 14, 2017|accessdate=December 15, 2017}}</ref> On December 14, 2018, Wawa opened a flagship location at 6th Street and [[Chestnut Street (Philadelphia)|Chestnut Street]] in [[Center City, Philadelphia]]. The store, at {{convert|11500|sqft|m2}}, is the largest Wawa location and features a living greenery wall, large digital screens, couches, caf\u00e9 seating, and two \"Philly Firsts\" murals.<ref>{{cite news|title=Largest Wawa ever opens in Center City Philadelphia|publisher=WPVI-TV|location=Philadelphia, PA|date=December 14, 2018|url=https://6abc.com/business/largest-wawa-ever-opens-in-center-city/4896910/|accessdate=December 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"150px\">\nFile:Wawa Market.jpg|An older Wawa in [[Sewell, New Jersey]]\nFile:Wawa in Wildwood, New Jersey.jpg|A retro-styled Wawa in [[Wildwood, New Jersey]]\nFile:First Orlando Wawa.jpg|A Wawa in [[Orlando, Florida]] on opening day\nFile:Wawa store at 6th and Chestnut streets Philadelphia.jpeg|The largest Wawa store, at 6th Street and [[Chestnut Street (Philadelphia)|Chestnut Street]] in [[Philadelphia|Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]\nFile:Urban Wawa in Washington, DC.jpg|Location in the [[Farragut Square]] neighborhood of [[downtown Washington, D.C.]]\n</gallery>\n\n== Data breach ==\nOn December 20, 2019, Wawa\u2019s CEO [[Chris Gheysens]] announced that the company had found malicious software on its payment processing servers that affected every location across the country, according to the statement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailypress.com/virginiagazette/va-vg-wawa-data-breach-20191220-um7tljrmnraxvh25st4gq7eiiu-story.html|title=Wawa gas stations announce credit card data breach that could affect every location nationwide|last=Jr|first=Steve Roberts|website=dailypress.com/virginiagazette|access-date=2019-12-21}}</ref> The malware is believed to have been on the servers since as early as March 4, 2019, and contained on December 12, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/12/20/wawa-says-data-breach-affected-thousands-over-10-months/|title=Wawa says data breach affected thousands over 10 months|last=Press|first=Associated|date=2019-12-20|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2019-12-21}}</ref>\n\nOn December 27, 2019, ''The Philadelphia Inquirer'' reported that at least six lawsuits seeking class-action status have been filed against the company in federal court in Philadelphia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2019/12/27/wawa-data-breach-convenience-store-chain-hit-customer-lawsuits/2759892001/|title=Wawa data breach: Convenience chain facing lawsuits over security incident at all of its stores|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal |last1= Steinberg|first1= Don|year= 2011|title= It's a Wawa World |journal=[[Philadelphia (magazine)|Philadelphia]] |volume= |issue= |pages= |publisher= [[Metrocorp]]|doi= |url=http://www.phillymag.com/restaurants/articles/it_s_a_wawa_world/ |accessdate=2011-08-29 }}\n* {{cite journal |last1= Bendapudi |first1= Neeli |last2=  Bendapudi|first2= Venkat |year=2005 |title=Creating the Living Brand |journal=[[Harvard Business Review]] |volume= |issue= |pages= |publisher=[[Harvard Business School Publishing]] |doi= |url= http://hbr.org/2005/05/creating-the-living-brand/ar/1|accessdate= 2011-08-29}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Wawa}}\n* {{Official website|www.wawa.com|mobile=http://m.wawa.com/WawaMobile/}}\n* [http://proguide.io/interview-with-howard-stoeckel-ceo-of-wawa-servant-leadership/ Interview with Howard about his Career]\n\n{{Philadelphia Corporations}}\n{{Convenience stores}}\n{{The Goldbergs}}\n{{Portal bar|Philadelphia|Pennsylvania|Companies|Food}}\n\n[[Category:Convenience stores of the United States]]\n[[Category:Cuisine of the Mid-Atlantic states]]\n[[Category:Economy of the Eastern United States]]\n[[Category:Fast-food chains of the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Delaware County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Gas stations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies based in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:1964 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1964]]\n[[Category:The Goldbergs (2013 TV series)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American convenience store chain}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Wawa, Inc.\n| logo             = [[File:Wawa logo.svg|200px]]\n| type             = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| founder          = Grahame Wood\n| location_city    = [[Wawa, Pennsylvania|Wawa]], [[Pennsylvania]]\n| location_country = United States<ref name=\"Forbes2017\"/>\n| area_served      = [[Mid-Atlantic states]], [[Florida]]\n| locations        = 842 stores (2019)<ref name=\"csnews.com\">{{cite web|url=https://csnews.com/top-100-convenience-store-chains-2019|title=Wawa Inc.|publisher=}}</ref><ref>http://csnews.com/wawa-test-smaller-c-store-format-philadelphia retrieved August 3, 2019</ref>\n| key_people       = [[Chris Gheysens]] ([[Chief Executive Officer|CEO]])<ref name=\"BestMet\">{{cite web|url=http://best-met.com/news/wawa-ceo-howard-stoeckel-retired-2012/ |title=Wawa CEO Howard Stoeckel To Retire At The End Of 2012 &#124; Food World &#124; Food Trade News |publisher=Best-met.com |date= |accessdate=2018-02-09}}</ref>\n| industry         = {{unbulleted list|[[Convenience store]]|[[Gas station]]|[[Fast food]]}}\n| products         = {{unbulleted list|Coffee|[[Submarine sandwich|Hoagies]]|Prepared foods|Gasoline|Beverages|Snacks|Dairy products|Salads}}\n| revenue          = {{profit}} [[US$]]10.6&nbsp;billion (2017)<ref name=\"Forbes2017\">{{cite web | url=https://www.forbes.com/companies/wawa/ | title=Wawa on the Forbes America's Best Employers 2019 List | publisher=Forbes | accessdate=May 18, 2019}}</ref>\n| net_income       = {{increase}} US$118 million (2011)<ref name=forbes>{{cite news |url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2011/21/private-companies-11_Wawa_ZHC5.html |title=#47 Wawa |year=2012 |work=[[Forbes]]}}</ref>\n| assets           = {{increase}} US$1.57 billion (2011)<ref name=forbes/>\n| num_employees    = 31,000 (2017)<ref name=\"Forbes2017\"/>\n| parent           = Wild Goose Holding Co.\n| homepage         = {{URL|www.wawa.com}}\n| logo_caption     = \n| image            = Wawa station in Montgomery County, Pennsylvania.jpg\n| image_caption    = Wawa gas station in [[Skippack, Pennsylvania]]\n| foundation       = {{Start date and age|1964|04|16}}\n}}\n\n'''Wawa, Inc.''' ({{IPAc-en|w|\u0251\u02d0|w|\u0251\u02d0}} {{respell|WAH-WAH}}) is an American chain of [[convenience store]]s and [[gas station]]s located along the [[East Coast of the United States]], operating in [[Pennsylvania]], [[New Jersey]], [[Delaware]], [[Maryland]], [[Virginia]], [[Washington, D.C.]], and [[Florida]].<ref name=\"AboutWawa\">{{cite web | url=https://www.wawa.com/About.aspx#aboutwawa | title=About Wawa | publisher=Wawa | date=2016 | accessdate=May 9, 2016}}</ref> The company's corporate headquarters is located in the [[Wawa, Pennsylvania|Wawa]] area of [[Chester Heights, Pennsylvania]] in [[Greater Philadelphia]].<!--Cited below--> {{As of|2008}}, Wawa was the largest convenience store chain in Greater Philadelphia, and it is also the third-largest retailer of food in Greater Philadelphia, after [[Acme Markets]] and [[ShopRite (United States)|ShopRite]].<ref name=\"Inquirer\">\"[http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=PI&s_site=philly&p_multi=PI&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F53D038D91AB567&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM Wawa's wonders of retailing,  The dairy and convenience-store chain is marking 100 years.]\" ''[[Philadelphia Inquirer]]''. August 5, 2002. D01. Retrieved on December 21, 2011. \"Wawa not only dominates the convenience-store business in the Philadelphia region but is also the third-largest food retailer, trailing only Acme Markets and ShopRite.\" and \"To boost sales, the company opened its first Wawa Food Market in 1964 in Folsom, Delaware County. Stores now spread from central Pennsylvania and central New Jersey to southern Virginia. In the 1970s, the company began selling more coffee by the cup,[...]\"</ref><ref name=\"Wood\">{{cite news|last=Wood|first=Anthony R.|title=A little dairy with a big idea How success came to Wawa|publisher=[[Philadelphia Inquirer]]|date=April 16, 2009|url=http://articles.philly.com/2009-04-16/news/25287891_1_wawa-coffee-sellers-professor-of-food-marketing|accessdate=December 21, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:WAWA.gif|thumb|left|Old Wawa logo used from 1990 to 2004. This logo is still in use at many locations.]]\nThe Wawa business began in 1803 as an iron [[foundry]].<ref name=\"AboutWawa\"/> In 1890, George Wood, an entrepreneur from [[New Jersey]],<ref name=\"Wawaplace3\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.philly.com/1989-06-15/news/26107992_1_franklin-mint-wawa-road-post-office/3 |title=Pay A Visit To Wawa, The Place |publisher=[[Philadelphia Inquirer]] |date=June 15, 1989|author=Mayer, Cynthia|accessdate=2018-12-09|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303234716/http://articles.philly.com/1989-06-15/news/26107992_1_franklin-mint-wawa-road-post-office|archive-date=March 3, 2016}}</ref> moved to [[Delaware County, Pennsylvania]]; it was here that he began the Wawa Dairy Farm.<ref name=\"Wawaplace3\"/> Wood imported [[Guernsey cattle|cows]] from the [[Crown dependencies|British Crown dependency]] island of [[Guernsey]], and bought {{convert|1000|acre|ha}} of land in the [[Chester Heights]] area;<ref name=\"Wawaplace3\"/> the corporate headquarters would later be renamed [[Wawa, Pennsylvania|Wawa]]. Since [[pasteurization]] was not yet available, many children faced sickness from consuming [[raw milk]]. Wood arranged for doctors to certify his milk was sanitary and safe for consumption, which convinced many consumers to buy the product.<ref name=\"Wawaplace3\"/> The strategy worked, and allowed the Wawa dairy to grow. Demand for dairy products grew rapidly during the 1920s, and so did the company. Wawa began using the slogan \"Buy Health by the Bottle\"; they served customers in Pennsylvania and New Jersey, delivering milk to customers' homes.\n\nIn the 1960s, however, many consumers began buying milk in stores instead of using home delivery. Wawa started to open its own stores to adjust to these market changes.<ref name=\"AboutWawa\"/><ref name=\"Wawaplace3\"/> On April 16, 1964, Grahame Wood, George Wood's grandson, opened the first Wawa Food Market at 1212 MacDade Boulevard in [[Folsom, Pennsylvania]],<ref name=\"WawaTimeline\"/> which remained in operation until June 17, 2016, when it closed in favor of a new \"Super Wawa\" down the street. A parade was held from the original location to the new store on opening day.<ref name=\"Wood\"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Ormsby|first=Barbara|title=Wawa closing its original store|work=[[Daily Local News]]|location=West Chester, PA|date=July 21, 2014|url=http://www.dailylocal.com/general-news/20140721/wawa-closing-its-original-store|accessdate=July 21, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"1StoreClose\">{{cite web |url=http://www.philly.com/philly/blogs/real-time/Wawas-1st-store-closes.html |title=Wawa's 1st store closes today |last=Babay |first=Emily |date=June 17, 2016 |website=Philly.com |publisher=Philadelphia Media Network |accessdate=January 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Wawa Food Market stores were also part of a then-new trend in retailing, the [[convenience store]]. Open both earlier and later than traditional [[supermarket]]s, they carried other foods and beverages besides milk, as well as other items from the Wawa dairy.\n[[File:Wawa Dairy Farms.JPG|thumb|The old Wawa Dairy Farms building in [[Wawa, Pennsylvania]]]]\n\nIn 1977, Wawa began sharing ownership of the company with its associates through [[profit-sharing]] plans. In 1992, Wawa formalized its associate ownership with its [[Employee Stock Ownership Plan]] (ESOP), with stock being awarded to associates annually based on the prior year's service. Because the company is privately held, Wawa secures an independent assessment of its stock value at regular intervals to ensure that the ESOP is fairly maintained.  Today, the ESOP accounts for more than 40% of Wawa stock.\n\n==Company==\n\n===Name and logo===\nThe [[store chain|chain]]'s name comes from the site of the company's first milk plant and corporate headquarters in the [[Wawa, Pennsylvania]] area. The name of the town ''Wawa'' is in turn derived from the [[Ojibwe]] word for the [[Canada goose]] (taken from ''[[The Song of Hiawatha]]'').{{citation needed|date=November 2017}} An image of a goose in flight serves as the Wawa [[corporate logo]]. It is said that the goose was chosen because the company employs the principles of teamwork, group consensus, and encouragement.\n\n===Leadership===\nThe current CEO of Wawa is [[Chris Gheysens]], who succeeded Howard Stoeckel in January 2013.<ref name=\"BestMet\"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://people.forbes.com/profile/howard-b-stoeckel/5363 |title=Howard B. Stoeckel Profile |accessdate=October 16, 2008 | work=Forbes}}</ref> [[Du Pont family|Eleuth\u00e8re (Th\u00e8re) du Pont]] has served as both the CFO and president, but is no longer associated with the company. Richard D. (Dick) Wood, Jr. is chairman of the [[board of directors]].  Many Wood family members are active in the company. Although Wawa is a [[family business|family-run business]], Wawa associates own roughly 50% of the company, more than 40% of which is owned through the company's employee stock-ownership program.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://getpocket.com/explore/item/the-inside-story-of-wawa-the-beloved-10-billion-convenience-store-chain-taking-over-the-east-coast|title=The Inside Story of Wawa, the Beloved $10 Billion Convenience Store Chain Taking Over the East Coast|accessdate=October 11, 2019| work=Inc}}</ref>\n\n===Holdings and locations===\n[[File:Wawa gas station Willow Grove PA.jpeg|thumb|right|A typical Wawa convenience store and gas station in [[Willow Grove, Pennsylvania]]]]\nIn 2015, Wawa ranked 34th on the ''[[Forbes]]'' magazine list of the largest [[private company|private companies]], with total revenues of $9.68 billion.<ref name=\"Forbes2015\">{{cite web | url=https://www.forbes.com/companies/wawa/ | title=Wawa on the Forbes America's Largest Private Companies List | publisher=Forbes | accessdate=March 27, 2016}}</ref> {{As of|2016}}, Wawa employs over 22,000 people<ref name=\"AboutWawa\"/><ref name=\"Forbes2015\"/> in 720+ stores (450+ offering gasoline).<ref name=\"WawaXfinity\">{{cite web | url=https://www.wawa.com/pdfs/042616_Comcast%20Wawa%20WiFi%20Press%20Release_FINAL.pdf | title=Wawa and Comcast team up to deliver free wi-fi at more than 700 East Coast locations | publisher=Wawa | date=April 26, 2016 | accessdate=May 9, 2016}}</ref> {{As of|2008}}, Wawa's New Jersey stores were concentrated mostly in [[South Jersey]].<!--Stick strictly to what the references say, please!--><ref>Strauss, Robert. \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/13/nyregion/nyregionspecial2/13movienj.html North Jersey or South? A Search for the Line].\" ''[[The New York Times]]''. July 13, 2008. Retrieved on December 23, 2011. \"There is the 'hoagie-sub' question: 'Hoagie' is a South Jersey term for a sandwich on a long roll, while a sub is the North Jersey version. No self-respecting North Jersey resident would know the Philadelphia Eagles fight song, and no South Jersey fan would wear a Giants T-shirt. Wawa stores dot the South, while North Jersey folks get their caffeine at a 7-11.\"</ref>\n\n{{As of|1989}} Wawa Inc. <!--\"Dated\" material should be kept-->and the Wood family together control about {{convert|725|acre|ha}} of land, containing the corporate headquarters, the Wawa dairy farm, and J.T. Farms, within two municipalities in [[Delaware County, Pennsylvania]]. The properties are located in [[Chester Heights, Pennsylvania|Chester Heights]] and [[Middletown Township, Delaware County, Pennsylvania|Middletown Township]]. Wawa Inc. owns {{convert|50|acre|ha}} of land around \"Red Roof,\" the corporate headquarters, {{convert|150|acre|ha}} of land around the Wawa dairy, and the {{convert|225|acre|ha|adj=on}} J.T. Farms. The Wood family owns {{convert|300|acre|ha}} of estate property. Cynthia Mayer of the ''[[Philadelphia Inquirer]]'' said that, as a result of the land holdings, the Wood family was \"the closest thing to a feudal barony this side of du Pont.\"<ref name=\"Wawaplace3\"/>\n\nBeginning in the 1940s, the dairy facility began selling excess parcels of land. In 1964, it sold about 40 acres to the [[Franklin Mint]]. Several years prior to 1989, the dairy sold 25 acres of land to a retirement complex, Granite Farms Estates. The process of selling excess land continued sporadically.\n\nWawa Inc. owns the 225-acre J.T. Farms, a separate farm property. {{As of|1989}} Wawa Inc. leases it to Bill Faul, who maintained a herd of 100 Holstein cattle and paid $1,500 (currently $2778.12) per month. Wawa continued to own the farm due to symbolic reasons. It also kept heifers along Route 1 in a strip of land adjacent to the plant which did not produce milk; Fritz Schroeder, then-vice president of Wawa Inc., said in 1989, \"[w]e like them for the ambiance.\"<ref name=\"Wawaplace4\">Mayer, Cynthia. \"Pay A Visit To Wawa, The Place.\" ''[[Philadelphia Inquirer]]''. June 15, 1989. D4. p. [http://articles.philly.com/1989-06-15/news/26107992_1_franklin-mint-wawa-road-post-office/4 4]. Retrieved on September 16, 2012.</ref>\n\nWawa, for the most part, covers parts of Pennsylvania not already served by fast-growing rival stores [[Sheetz]], [[Rutter's]], and [[Turkey Hill Minit Markets|Turkey Hill]]. Wawa is often compared to Sheetz due to their similar business models and Pennsylvania roots.<ref name=\"Sheetz\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.philly.com/2013-04-01/business/38165625_1_lou-sheetz-dairy-farm-coffee-business |title=Archives - Philly.com |publisher=Articles.philly.com |date= |accessdate=2018-02-09}}</ref>\n\n====Corporate headquarters====\n[[File:Wawa Red Roof.JPG|thumb|\"Red Roof\" at Wawa headquarters in [[Chester Heights, Pennsylvania]]]]\nThe company's corporate headquarters is located in the [[Wawa, Pennsylvania|Wawa]] area, along [[Baltimore Pike]]<ref name=\"Wawaplace1\">Mayer, Cynthia. \"Pay A Visit To Wawa, The Place.\" ''[[Philadelphia Inquirer]]''. June 15, 1989. D4. p. [http://articles.philly.com/1989-06-15/news/26107992_1_franklin-mint-wawa-road-post-office 1]. Retrieved on September 16, 2012.</ref><ref>\"[http://www.wawa.com/WawaWeb/About.aspx About Wawa] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140317200208/http://www.wawa.com/WawaWeb/About.aspx |date=March 17, 2014 }}.\" Wawa Inc. Retrieved on February 18, 2011. \"Headquarters Red Roof, Baltimore Pike Wawa, Pennsylvania 19063.\"</ref> in [[Chester Heights, Pennsylvania|Chester Heights]].<ref name=Starkoptions>Stark, Kenn. \"[http://delcotimes.com/articles/2011/12/05/news/doc4edd3e6cc214b403007473.txt Chester Heights mulls options in light of proposed tax hike].\" ''[[Delaware County Daily Times]]''. Monday December 5, 2011. Retrieved on September 16, 2012. \"Currently, about 300 Wawa employees work at the Red Roof corporate headquarters in Chester Heights.\"</ref><ref>\"[http://www.chesterheights.org/Zoning%20Map.html Borough of Chester Heights Zoning Map].\" ([https://www.webcitation.org/6Aj5rtdLf?url=http://www.chesterheights.org/Zoning-Page.jpg Archive]) [[Borough of Chester Heights]]. Retrieved on September 16, 2012.</ref> The headquarters is in proximity to [[Middletown Township, Delaware County, Pennsylvania|Middletown Township]].<ref name=\"NYTBan\">\"[https://www.nytimes.com/1999/05/09/us/stores-post-billboard-ads-for-tobacco-despite-ban.html Stores Post Billboard Ads for Tobacco, Despite Ban].\" ''[[The New York Times]]''. May 9, 1999. Retrieved on December 23, 2011.</ref> {{As of|2011}} about 300 employees work in the headquarters. The Borough of Chester Heights receives a majority of its local services tax from employees of Wawa.<ref name=Starkoptions/>\n\n==Programs and promotions==\nWawa provides surcharge-free ATMs, the result of a partnership with [[PNC Bank]] that began in 1985. Wawa implemented the program in stores in 1996. In 2010, Wawa surpassed 1 billion transactions under the PNC brand.<ref name=\"ATMMarketplace\">{{cite web | url=http://www.atmmarketplace.com/article/127662/Wawa-hits-1-billion-ATM-transactions-with-PNC-brand | title=Wawa hits 1 billion ATM transactions with PNC brand | publisher=Networld Media Group | work=ATM Marketplace | date=April 19, 2010 | accessdate=May 9, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201170357/http://www.atmmarketplace.com/article/127662/Wawa-hits-1-billion-ATM-transactions-with-PNC-brand |archive-date=February 1, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the late 1980s and through the 1990s, Wawa engaged in a scholarship sponsorship program that involved Irish students (mainly from [[University College Cork|UCC]] in Cork, Ireland) running some stores on the Pennsylvania Main Line, allowing the students to study for their MBAs from Saint Joseph's University in Philadelphia.<ref name=\"SJUScholarship\">{{cite web | url=http://www.sju.edu/ucomm/archives/2003/december/hawkeye_12082003.html | title=Scholarship Program Links SJU and Northern Ireland | publisher=[[Saint Joseph's University]] | work=HawkEye | date=December 8, 2003 | accessdate=May 9, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927003905/http://www.sju.edu/ucomm/archives/2003/december/hawkeye_12082003.html |archive-date=September 27, 2007}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Wawa coffee bar.jpg|thumb|left|upright|A Wawa coffee bar counter with different flavors. A staple of Wawa stores for years, the glass carafes were replaced with coffee dispensers around 2010.]]\n\nIn 1994, Wawa opened a store in [[Center City, Philadelphia]], which sold food only.<ref name=\"Westfeldt\">Westfeldt, Amy. \"[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=O5c_AAAAIBAJ&sjid=CFYMAAAAIBAJ&pg=5174,5376452&dq=wawa+pennsylvania+institution&hl=en Convenience Stores in the '90s].\" ''[[Associated Press]]'' at the ''[[Warsaw Times-Union]]''. Saturday July 27, 1996. 10C. Retrieved from [[Google News]] (14/39) on January 1, 2011.</ref>\n\nIn 1994, Wawa debuted the \"Super Wawa\", larger stores with public restrooms and more parking. Gasoline pumps were added in 1996.<ref name=\"BCTWawa\">{{cite news | url=http://www.burlingtoncountytimes.com/business/wawa-history-through-the-years/article_b4abed32-c050-51f0-bd29-ee3711d8d1aa.html | title=Wawa history through the years | work=[[Burlington County Times]] | date=April 16, 2014 | accessdate=May 9, 2016 | author=Bishop, Chris}}</ref><ref name=\"WawaTimeline\">{{cite web | url=https://www.wawa.com/wawatimeline.aspx | title=Wawa Timeline | publisher=Wawa | date=2014 | accessdate=May 9, 2016}}</ref> On October 21, 2010, Wawa began testing the sale of [[diesel fuel]] at 12 of its New Jersey locations due to an increasing number of cars using this fuel.<ref name=\"CSPNews\">{{cite web | url=http://www.cspnet.com/ME2/Audiences/dirmod.asp?sid=&nm=&type=Publishing&mod=Publications::Article&mid=8F3A7027421841978F18BE895F87F791&AudID=CBA745B91AFB44FA923476ACBBD040A5&tier=4&id=E6DDDEBA76D9433B9D01DFF2677E37CB | title=Wawa Mulling Diesel Deal | publisher=CSP Daily News | date=October 22, 2010 | accessdate=May 9, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708212809/http://www.cspnet.com/ME2/Audiences/dirmod.asp?sid=&nm=&type=Publishing&mod=Publications::Article&mid=8F3A7027421841978F18BE895F87F791&AudID=CBA745B91AFB44FA923476ACBBD040A5&tier=4&id=E6DDDEBA76D9433B9D01DFF2677E37CB | archive-date=July 8, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2000s, Wawa was among the first stores to implement [[self-serve]] computer [[touch-screen]] menus for food orders, in an attempt to improve order accuracy, speed and for upselling.<ref name=\"Screen\">{{cite web | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/goingoutguide/why-you-may-soon-be-ordering-lunch-on-a-touch-screen-kiosk/2017/03/01/0b964a90-f915-11e6-bf01-d47f8cf9b643_story.html|title= Why touch screens are changing how we order at restaurants |date=March 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, Wawa and [[McLane Company#Customers|McLane Co.]] reached a 30-year agreement to construct a distribution center in [[Carney's Point, New Jersey]], to handle the majority of Wawa's distribution.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.foodlogistics.com/article/10255783/golden-pallet-award |title=Golden Pallet Award - A Unique Partnership That Delivers |author=Katherine Doherty |date=September 9, 2009|work= |publisher=Food Logistics |accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"McLaneWhitePaper\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mclaneco.com/www/AnonDocs/Solutions/ThirdParty/WAWA_whitepaper.pdf |title=Business Case: Third-Party Supply Chain Solutions |author=McLane Company |date=April 2009 |publisher=McLane Company |accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref> The center began operation in May 2004.<ref name=\"McLaneWhitePaper\"/>\n\nIn 2005, Wawa partnered with JPMorgan Chase to offer a Visa credit card branded with the Wawa name. It ceased issuing new cards in December 2007 and the program was canceled in November 2010.<ref>\"[http://www.philly.com/philly/blogs/inq-phillydeals/Bank_cancels_Wawas_credit_cards.html Wawa's credit cards canceled].\" ''[[Philadelphia Inquirer]]''. October 14, 2010. Retrieved on November 24, 2010.</ref> Wawa would later partner with Citi to restart the Wawa credit card program.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wawa.com/wawacreditcard/ |title=Credit Card: Save on Fuel with the Wawa Gas Credit Card |publisher=Wawa |date= |accessdate=2018-02-09}}</ref>\n\nWawa moved into social media to connect with its customers, and in 2006, its \"I Love Wawa\" MySpace page had over 5,000 members. By the middle of 2013, its Facebook page had reached nearly 1.1 million likes.<ref>Walker, Rob. \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2006/07/30/magazine/30wwln_consumed.html Convenience Cult?]\" ''[[The New York Times]]''. July 30, 2006. Retrieved on December 23, 2011.</ref>\n\nOn June 30, 2010, 20 Wawa locations in Pennsylvania started a trial of selling [[Pennsylvania Lottery]] tickets from automated kiosks. On December 6, 2010, it announced that all 210 Pennsylvania Wawa locations would sell lottery tickets from kiosks by spring 2011.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.csnews.com/tmp-financial/wawa-expands-pennsylvania-lottery-program | title=Wawa Expands Pennsylvania Lottery Program | publisher=Stagnito Media | work=ConvenienceStoreNews | date=December 6, 2010 | accessdate=April 15, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nbcphiladelphia.com/news/politics/Wawas-Across-PA-Get-Lottery-Kiosks-111407039.html | title=Wawa Bets on Pa. Lottery | publisher=[[NBCUniversal]] | work=[[WCAU|NBC 10]] | date=December 6, 2010 | accessdate=April 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn April 16, 2014, to celebrate its 50th anniversary, Wawa gave away free coffee and launched a nonprofit foundation to donate $50 million to health and hunger initiatives.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcall.com/news/breaking/mc-wawa-anniversary-free-coffee-20140416,0,3265420.story |title= Free coffee at Wawa to mark 50th anniversary |publisher=[[The Morning Call]]|date=April 16, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Products==\nWawa offers products found at most convenience chain marts such as chips, drinks, and soda. Wawa also sells its own branded iced tea, orange juice, and milk. Wawa used to sell its own branded soda but it has been discontinued. Wawa has [[Coca-Cola Freestyle]] soda fountains.\n\nKey products include its variety of coffee, latte, and cappuccino flavors and sizes, and made-to-order [[hoagies]]. Wawa also offers a brand of hot breakfast products, most famous of which is the \"Sizzli\", and also a full [[Delicatessen|deli]] with touch-screen ordering of sandwiches, hot sides, drinks, and deli meats. Wawa sells alcohol in Florida, Virginia, and at one Pennsylvania location in [[Chadds Ford, Pennsylvania|Chadds Ford]].<ref name=\"DelCoTimesBeer\">{{cite news | url=http://www.delcotimes.com/article/DC/20150614/NEWS/150619814 | title=Wawa hops into the beer-sales market | work=[[Delaware County Daily Times]] | date=June 14, 2015 | accessdate=May 9, 2016 | author=Logue, Tim}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Wilson|first=Shawnette|title=Chadds Ford Wawa Soon To Sell Beer|publisher=WTXF-TV|location=Philadelphia, PA|date=August 4, 2015|url=http://www.fox29.com/news/chadds-ford-wawa-soon-to-sell-beer#/|accessdate=January 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFor a short time between 1994 and 1996, Wawa sold [[Pizza Hut]] Personal Pan Pizzas and [[Taco Bell]] burritos.<ref name=\"Westfeldt\"/>\n\nIn 2018, Wawa introduced a [[secret menu]] to celebrate its 54th anniversary. It can be accessed by tapping the flapping goose in the bottom left corner of the ordering screen. As of June 2018, it contains a Birthday Cake Smoothie, a Birthday Cake Milkshake, and a Mac & Cheese Cheesesteak.\n\n==Store locations==\n[[File:Wawa footprint 2019-12.png|thumb|Wawa footprint as of December 2019]]\nWawa operates stores in [[Delaware]], [[Florida]], [[Maryland]], [[South Jersey|Southern New Jersey]], [[Pennsylvania]], [[Virginia]], and [[Washington, D.C.]] Wawa's territory once stretched into [[North Jersey|Northern New Jersey]], [[New York (state)|New York]] and [[Connecticut]], but in the late 1990s, the decision was made to abandon the franchised stores in the [[New York metropolitan area]] and [[New England]], as it was too competitive. The abandoned stores were re-branded when they were sold to Krauszer's (in Connecticut) and a variety of other convenience retailers, but most are still recognizable as they retain their distinctive \"Wawa\" design. The company continued to operate numerous stores in [[Central Jersey]] and South Jersey, and re-entered North Jersey in 2010, when Wawa opened a new store in [[Parsippany, New Jersey|Parsippany]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Paik|first=Eugene|url=http://www.nj.com/news/local/index.ssf/2010/06/wawas_parsippany_store_will_be.html|title=Wawa's Parsippany store will be its northern-most location|publisher=[[The Star-Ledger]]|date=June 14, 2010|accessdate=December 16, 2010}}</ref> Wawa opened its 100th Super Wawa in New Jersey on October 12, 2012, in [[Woodbridge, New Jersey|Woodbridge]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Bell|first=Deborah|url=http://woodbridge.patch.com/articles/wawa-set-to-open-in-ford-on-friday|title=Wawa Set to Open New Fords Store This Friday|work=Woodbridge Patch|date=October 9, 2012|accessdate=December 21, 2012}}</ref> Wawa moved farther into North Jersey opening in [[Kearny, New Jersey|Kearny]] on January 11, 2013, and [[Lodi, New Jersey|Lodi]] on October 4, 2013. The company plans to open five Wawas a year in North Jersey for the next 10 to 12 years.<ref>{{cite news|last=Genovese|first=Peter|url=http://www.nj.com/news/index.ssf/2013/01/wawa_in_mahwah_some_day_chain.html|title=Wawa in Mahwah some day? Chain invades North Jersey |work=[[The Star-Ledger]]|date=January 11, 2013|accessdate=January 12, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn July 18, 2012, Wawa entered the Florida market when it opened its first location in [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cfnews13.com/content/news/cfnews13/news/article.html/content/news/articles/cfn/2012/7/18/florida_s_first_wawa.html|title=Florida's first Wawa opens today in Orlando, Orlando|work=Central Florida News 13|date=July 18, 2012}}</ref> It had expanded to more than 70 Florida locations by the end of 2015, with plans for 120 more by 2022.<ref name=\"SSWawa\">{{cite web | url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/business/consumer/fl-wawa-south-florida-plans-20151109-story.html | title=Wawa plans 120 stores in South Florida | work=[[Sun Sentinel]] | date=November 9, 2015 | accessdate=July 1, 2016 | author=Valverde, Miriam}}</ref>\n\n{{As of|2018|05}}, Wawa has over 800 locations across Delaware, Maryland, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Virginia, and Florida.<ref name=\"csnews.com\"/>\n\nIn some [[Jersey Shore]] towns, Wawa designs its stores to match the aesthetic, and changes operating procedures to adapt to shore culture. In [[Cape May, New Jersey|Cape May]], Wawa has a Victorian-themed store. In [[Wildwood, New Jersey|Wildwood]], there is a 1950s-themed store.<ref name=\"Warner1\">{{cite news|last=Warner|first=Susan|title=Mom and Pop Hold Sway At the Shore|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=August 14, 2005|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/14/nyregion/nyregionspecial2/14njCHAINS.html?pagewanted=all |accessdate=December 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\nWawa opened its largest location at the time in the [[Farragut Square]] area of Washington, D.C. on December 14, 2017.<ref>{{cite news|last=Aggarwal|first=Nehal|url=https://www.washingtonian.com/2017/12/14/dcs-first-wawa-opens-with-selfie-screens-and-nitro-coffee/|title=DC\u2019s First Wawa Opens With Selfie-Screens and Nitro Coffee|work=[[Washingtonian (magazine)|Washingtonian]]|date=December 14, 2017|accessdate=December 15, 2017}}</ref> On December 14, 2018, Wawa opened a flagship location at 6th Street and [[Chestnut Street (Philadelphia)|Chestnut Street]] in [[Center City, Philadelphia]]. The store, at {{convert|11500|sqft|m2}}, is the largest Wawa location and features a living greenery wall, large digital screens, couches, caf\u00e9 seating, and two \"Philly Firsts\" murals.<ref>{{cite news|title=Largest Wawa ever opens in Center City Philadelphia|publisher=WPVI-TV|location=Philadelphia, PA|date=December 14, 2018|url=https://6abc.com/business/largest-wawa-ever-opens-in-center-city/4896910/|accessdate=December 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\n<gallery widths=\"200px\" heights=\"150px\">\nFile:Wawa Market.jpg|An older Wawa in [[Sewell, New Jersey]]\nFile:Wawa in Wildwood, New Jersey.jpg|A retro-styled Wawa in [[Wildwood, New Jersey]]\nFile:First Orlando Wawa.jpg|A Wawa in [[Orlando, Florida]] on opening day\nFile:Wawa store at 6th and Chestnut streets Philadelphia.jpeg|The largest Wawa store, at 6th Street and [[Chestnut Street (Philadelphia)|Chestnut Street]] in [[Philadelphia|Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]]\nFile:Urban Wawa in Washington, DC.jpg|Location in the [[Farragut Square]] neighborhood of [[downtown Washington, D.C.]]\n</gallery>\n\n== Data breach ==\nOn December 20, 2019, Wawa\u2019s CEO [[Chris Gheysens]] announced that the company had found malicious software on its payment processing servers that affected every location across the country, according to the statement.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dailypress.com/virginiagazette/va-vg-wawa-data-breach-20191220-um7tljrmnraxvh25st4gq7eiiu-story.html|title=Wawa gas stations announce credit card data breach that could affect every location nationwide|last=Jr|first=Steve Roberts|website=dailypress.com/virginiagazette|access-date=2019-12-21}}</ref> The malware is believed to have been on the servers since as early as March 4, 2019, and contained on December 12, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/12/20/wawa-says-data-breach-affected-thousands-over-10-months/|title=Wawa says data breach affected thousands over 10 months|last=Press|first=Associated|date=2019-12-20|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2019-12-21}}</ref>\n\nOn December 27, 2019, ''The Philadelphia Inquirer'' reported that at least six lawsuits seeking class-action status have been filed against the company in federal court in Philadelphia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2019/12/27/wawa-data-breach-convenience-store-chain-hit-customer-lawsuits/2759892001/|title=Wawa data breach: Convenience chain facing lawsuits over security incident at all of its stores|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite journal |last1= Steinberg|first1= Don|year= 2011|title= It's a Wawa World |journal=[[Philadelphia (magazine)|Philadelphia]] |volume= |issue= |pages= |publisher= [[Metrocorp]]|doi= |url=http://www.phillymag.com/restaurants/articles/it_s_a_wawa_world/ |accessdate=2011-08-29 }}\n* {{cite journal |last1= Bendapudi |first1= Neeli |last2=  Bendapudi|first2= Venkat |year=2005 |title=Creating the Living Brand |journal=[[Harvard Business Review]] |volume= |issue= |pages= |publisher=[[Harvard Business School Publishing]] |doi= |url= http://hbr.org/2005/05/creating-the-living-brand/ar/1|accessdate= 2011-08-29}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Wawa}}\n* {{Official website|www.wawa.com|mobile=http://m.wawa.com/WawaMobile/}}\n* [http://proguide.io/interview-with-howard-stoeckel-ceo-of-wawa-servant-leadership/ Interview with Howard about his Career]\n\n{{Philadelphia Corporations}}\n{{Convenience stores}}\n{{The Goldbergs}}\n{{Portal bar|Philadelphia|Pennsylvania|Companies|Food}}\n\n[[Category:Convenience stores of the United States]]\n[[Category:Cuisine of the Mid-Atlantic states]]\n[[Category:Economy of the Eastern United States]]\n[[Category:Fast-food chains of the United States]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Delaware County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Gas stations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies based in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:1964 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Retail companies established in 1964]]\n[[Category:The Goldbergs (2013 TV series)]]\n", "name_user": "72.73.237.212", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eName and logo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wawa_(company)"}
{"title_page": "Henry J. Friel", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Henry James Friel\n| image =\n| imagesize = 150\n| caption = \n| birth_date =15 April 1823\n| birth_place = [[Montreal, Quebec]]\n| death_date = 16 May 1869\n| death_place = [[Ottawa, Ontario]]\n| office =  [[Mayor of Ottawa|Mayor of Bytown]]\n| office2 =  [[Mayor of Ottawa]]\n| office3 =  [[Mayor of Ottawa]]\n| term_start = 1854 \n| term_end =1854  \n| term_start2 =1863\n| term_end2 =1864 \n| term_start3 =1868\n| term_end3 = 1869\n| predecessor = Joseph-Balsora Turgeon\n| successor = [[John Bower Lewis]]\n| predecessor2 =[[Alexander Workman]]\n| successor2 = [[Moss Kent Dickinson]]\n| predecessor3 =[[Robert Lyon (politician)|Robert Lyon]]\n| successor3 = [[John Rochester (politician)|John Rochester]]\n| party = \n| religion = Roman Catholic\n| constituency = \n| majority = \n| spouse = \n}}\n'''Henry James Friel''' (15 April 1823 &ndash; 16 May 1869) was [[mayor]] of Bytown in 1854 and then of [[Ottawa]] in 1863 and 1868\u20131869.<ref>Dave Mullington \"Chain of Office: Biographic Sketches of Ottawa's Mayors (1847-1948)\" (Renfrew, Ontario: General Store Publishing House, 2005)</ref>\n\nHe was born in [[Montreal]] of [[Ireland|Irish]] [[roman catholic|Catholic]] parents Charles Friel and Cecila Brennan on 15 April 1823. His family moved to Bytown, which was later renamed Ottawa, in 1827.\n\n== Political life ==\nFriel was [[1847 Bytown municipal election|elected to Bytown's first town council in 1847]]. He was defeated the following year, but elected [[alderman]] in 1850, 1853 and 1854, when he was elected mayor. He also served on the executive of the [[Bytown Mechanics' Institute]].\n\nThe municipality of Bytown became the new city of Ottawa in 1855. Friel was elected alderman there from 1855 to 1858 and in 1864, 1865 and 1867. In 1863, he was a member of the first Board of Police Commissioners for Ottawa. The board, with the aim of avoiding unnecessary expense, originally concluded that there was no need for a salaried police force in the city. However, in May that same year, the militia had to be called in to control a riot in the city. In 1865, a bylaw was introduced establishing an official police force. In 1868, while mayor, Friel posted a proclamation announcing a $2,000 reward for information leading to the conviction of the assassin of [[Thomas D'Arcy McGee]].\n\n== Professional life ==\nIn 1846, he purchased the ''[[Bytown Packet]]'', a local newspaper, with John George Bell. He sold this paper in October 1849 to Robert Bell, who renamed it the ''[[Ottawa Citizen]]'' in 1849. In 1858, he established a new paper, the ''Ottawa Union'', also referred to as the ''Daily Union''. He later sold it to a rival paper, the ''Ottawa Times'' in 1866.\n\n== Personal life ==\nHe died in Ottawa in 1869 of [[pneumonia]] while still in office. His funeral sermon was delivered in [[Notre-Dame Cathedral (Ottawa)]] on Wednesday, 19 May 1869 by Aeneas Mcdonell Dawson.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n;Bibliography\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Citation\n        |last = Dawson\n        |first = Aeneas Mcdonell \n        |title = Sermon Delivered In The Cathedral Of Ottawa At The Funeral Of The Late H. J. Friel, Esq., Mayor Of Ottawa, On Wednesday, 19th May, 1869 by Aeneas Mcdonell Dawson\n        |date = August 17, 2011 \n        |publisher =Nabu Press This is a pre-1923 historical reproduction \n        |publication-place =Ottawa, Ontario\n        |isbn = \n        }}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Ontario}}\n*[http://www.biographi.ca/009004-119.01-e.php?&id_nbr=4438 Biography at the ''Dictionary of Canadian Biography Online'']\n\n{{Ottawamayor}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Friel, Henry}}\n[[Category:1823 births]]\n[[Category:1869 deaths]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Ottawa]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Montreal]]\n[[Category:Writers from Montreal]]\n[[Category:Ottawa city councillors]]\n[[Category:Ottawa Citizen people]]\n[[Category:19th-century journalists]]\n[[Category:Male journalists]]\n[[Category:19th-century male writers]]\n\n\n{{Ontario-mayor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Henry James Friel\n| image =\n| imagesize = 150\n| caption = \n| birth_date =15 April 1823\n| birth_place = [[Montreal, Quebec]]\n| death_date = 16 May 1869\n| death_place = [[Ottawa, Ontario]]\n| office =  [[Mayor of Ottawa|Mayor of Bytown]]\n| office2 =  [[Mayor of Ottawa]]\n| office3 =  [[Mayor of Ottawa]]\n| term_start = 1854 \n| term_end =1854  \n| term_start2 =1863\n| term_end2 =1864 \n| term_start3 =1868\n| term_end3 = 1869\n| predecessor = Joseph-Balsora Turgeon\n| successor = [[John Bower Lewis]]\n| predecessor2 =[[Alexander Workman]]\n| successor2 = [[Moss Kent Dickinson]]\n| predecessor3 =[[Robert Lyon (politician)|Robert Lyon]]\n| successor3 = [[John Rochester (politician)|John Rochester]]\n| party = \n| religion = Roman Catholic\n| constituency = \n| majority = \n| spouse = \n}}\n'''Henry James Friel''' (15 April 1823 &ndash; 16 May 1869) was [[mayor]] of Bytown in 1854 and then of [[Ottawa]] in 1863 and 1868-1869.<ref>Dave Mullington \"Chain of Office: Biographic Sketches of Ottawa's Mayors (1847-1948)\" (Renfrew, Ontario: General Store Publishing House, 2005)</ref>\n\nHe was born in [[Montreal]] of [[Ireland|Irish]] [[roman catholic|Catholic]] parents Charles Friel and Cecila Brennan on 15 April 1823. His family moved to Bytown, which was later renamed Ottawa, in 1827.\n\n== Political Life ==\nFriel was [[1847 Bytown municipal election|elected to Bytown's first town council in 1847]]. He was defeated the following year, but elected [[alderman]] in 1850, 1853 and 1854, when he was elected mayor. He also served on the executive of the [[Bytown Mechanics' Institute]].\n\nThe municipality of Bytown became the new city of Ottawa in 1855. Friel was elected alderman there from 1855 to 1858 and in 1864, 1865 and 1867. In 1863, he was a member of the first Board of Police Commissioners for Ottawa. The board, with the aim of avoiding unnecessary expense, originally concluded that there was no need for a salaried police force in the city. However, in May that same year, the militia had to be called in to control a riot in the city. In 1865, a bylaw was introduced establishing an official police force. In 1868, while mayor, Friel posted a proclamation announcing a $2,000 reward for information leading to the conviction of the assassin of [[Thomas D'Arcy McGee]].\n\n== Professional Life ==\nIn 1846, he purchased the [[Bytown Packet]], a local newspaper, with John George Bell. He sold this paper in October 1849 to Robert Bell, who renamed it the ''[[Ottawa Citizen]]'' in 1849. In 1858, he established a new paper, the ''Ottawa Union'', also referred to as the ''Daily Union''. He later sold it to a rival paper, the ''Ottawa Times'' in 1866.\n\n== Personal life ==\nHe died in Ottawa in 1869 of [[pneumonia]] while still in office. His funeral sermon was delivered in [[Notre-Dame Cathedral (Ottawa)]] on Wednesday, 19 May 1869 by Aeneas Mcdonell Dawson.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n;Bibliography\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Citation\n        |last = Dawson\n        |first = Aeneas Mcdonell \n        |title = Sermon Delivered In The Cathedral Of Ottawa At The Funeral Of The Late H. J. Friel, Esq., Mayor Of Ottawa, On Wednesday, 19th May, 1869 by Aeneas Mcdonell Dawson\n        |date = August 17, 2011 \n        |publisher =Nabu Press This is a pre-1923 historical reproduction \n        |publication-place =Ottawa, Ontario\n        |isbn = \n        }}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Ontario}}\n*[http://www.biographi.ca/009004-119.01-e.php?&id_nbr=4438 Biography at the ''Dictionary of Canadian Biography Online'']\n\n{{Ottawamayor}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Friel, Henry}}\n[[Category:1823 births]]\n[[Category:1869 deaths]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Ottawa]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Montreal]]\n[[Category:Writers from Montreal]]\n[[Category:Ottawa city councillors]]\n[[Category:Ottawa Citizen people]]\n[[Category:19th-century journalists]]\n[[Category:Male journalists]]\n[[Category:19th-century male writers]]\n\n\n{{Ontario-mayor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "replaced: 1868-1869 \u2192 1868\u20131869, Life \u2192 life, Life \u2192 life; italics", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_J._Friel"}
{"title_page": "Interstate 840 (Tennessee)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Highway in Tennessee}}\n{{Infobox road\n|state=TN\n|type=I\n|route=840\n|alternate_name= Tennessee National Guard Parkway\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-height=250|frame-lat=35.998|frame-long=-86.808|zoom=8|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/Interstate 840 (Tennessee)}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=I-840 highlighted in red\n|length_mi=77.28\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"840hold\"/>\n|established=August 12, 2016\n|spur_type=I\n|spur_of=40\n|direction_a=West\n|terminus_a={{jct|state=TN|I|40}} near [[Dickson, Tennessee|Dickson]]\n|junction={{plainlist|1=\n*{{jct|state=TN|I|65}} near [[Franklin, Tennessee|Franklin]]\n*{{jct|state=TN|I|24}} near [[Murfreesboro, Tennessee|Murfreesboro]] }}\n|direction_b=East\n|terminus_b={{jct|state=TN|I|40}} near [[Lebanon, Tennessee|Lebanon]]\n|counties=[[Dickson County, Tennessee|Dickson]], [[Hickman County, Tennessee|Hickman]], [[Williamson County, Tennessee|Williamson]], [[Rutherford County, Tennessee|Rutherford]], [[Wilson County, Tennessee|Wilson]]\n|previous_type=US\n|previous_route=641\n|next_type=SR\n|next_route=1\n}}\n'''Interstate 840''' ('''I-840'''), formerly '''State Route 840''' ('''SR&nbsp;840'''), also designated as '''Tennessee National Guard Parkway''',<ref name=\"enjoytheride\">{{cite book |author = Tennessee Department of Transportation |year = 2012 |url = http://www.tdot.state.tn.us/sr840s/docs/840book11-1.pdf |title = State Route&nbsp;840: Enjoy the Ride |type = Dedication program |publisher = Tennessee Department of Transportation |access-date = June 12, 2015 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121119032423/http://www.tdot.state.tn.us/sr840s/docs/840book11-1.pdf |archive-date = November 19, 2012 }}</ref> is a loop interstate highway around [[Nashville, Tennessee]], built by the [[Tennessee Department of Transportation]] (TDOT). First proposed by former Governor [[Lamar Alexander]] as part of a system of Bicentennial Parkways, construction began in 1991 and was completed in 2012. The [[freeway]] is {{convert|77.28|mi|km}} long,<ref name=\"840hold\"/> and it serves the cities of [[Lebanon, Tennessee|Lebanon]], [[Murfreesboro, Tennessee|Murfreesboro]], [[Franklin, Tennessee|Franklin]], and [[Dickson, Tennessee|Dickson]].<ref name=TDOT>{{cite map |author = Tennessee Department of Transportation |year = 2014 |title = Tennessee: 2014 Official Transportation Map |scale = c. 1:633,600 |location = Nashville |publisher = Tennessee Department of Transportation |sections = C7\u2013B8 }}</ref><ref name=gm>{{google maps |url = https://www.google.com/maps/dir/36.0215803,-87.2653359/36.1836542,-86.3521029/@35.993783,-86.78102,11z/data=!4m9!4m8!1m5!3m4!1m2!1d-86.7223008!2d35.8338299!3s0x88638866c916df7d:0x63cd9e63c74868ca!1m0!3e0 |title = State Route&nbsp;840 |access-date = June 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOriginally planned as an interstate highway, I-840 was constructed entirely with state funds and as a result was initially designated as a state route.<ref name=\"enjoytheride\"/> In 2015, approval was given by the [[Federal Highway Administration]] (FHWA) and the [[American Association of State Highway and Transportation Officials]] (AASHTO) to redesignate SR&nbsp;840 as Interstate&nbsp;840 (I-840) as part of its integration into the [[Interstate Highway System]]. On August 12, 2016, TDOT announced that it would begin re-signing the route on August 14 and that work would be complete later in the year.\n\n==Route description==\nI-840 begins at an interchange in [[Dickson County, Tennessee|Dickson County]] near Dickson. It initially runs southeast through a predominantly hilly terrain, and comes to an interchange with [[Tennessee State Route 100|State Route 100]] (SR 100) about {{convert|7.3|mi|km}} later. About ten miles later it crosses the [[Natchez Trace Parkway]] and turns east. I-840 has an interchange with [[U.S. Route 31 in Tennessee|U.S. Route 31]] (US 31) about ten miles later, and about {{convert|3|mi|km}} later comes to an interchange with [[Interstate 65 in Tennessee|I-65]] south of Franklin in an interchange that resembles a [[cloverstack interchange]], containing two loop ramps and two underpass ramps that cross I-840 combined together. The route continues through a hilly terrain with several steep grades, and comes to an interchange with [[U.S. Route 31 Alternate (Tennessee)|US 31 Alternate]] and [[U.S. Route 41 Alternate (Monteagle, Tennessee \u2013 Hopkinsville, Kentucky)|41 Alternate]] about {{convert|11|mi|km}} later. About {{convert|3|mi|km}} later I-840 crosses [[Tennessee State Route 96|State Route 96]] (SR 96), and about {{convert|9|mi|km}} later comes to an interchange with I-24 southwest of [[Murfreesboro, Tennessee|Murfreesboro]]. This interchange is almost a complete [[cloverleaf interchange|cloverleaf]], containing three loop ramps and one [[overpass|flyover]]. The route turns northeast, passing through a predominantly rural and agricultural area, and about {{convert|19|mi|km}} later comes to an interchange with [[Tennessee State Route 109|State Route 109]] (SR 109). The route turns slightly northeast, and about {{convert|3.8|mi|km}} later reaches its eastern terminus with I-40 in [[Wilson County, Tennessee|Wilson County]] west of Lebanon.<ref name=google>{{google maps |url = https://www.google.com/maps/place/I-840,+Tennessee/@36.0861572,-86.596612,66351m/data=!3m1!1e3!4m5!3m4!1s0x88647b9afed8536b:0x963e9004ea8fed0f!8m2!3d36.0895955!4d-86.427016 |title = I-840 |access-date = December 18, 2017 |link = no }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{Infobox road small\n|state=TN\n|type=SR\n|route=840\n|location=[[Dickson, Tennessee|Dickson]]\u2013[[Lebanon, Tennessee|Lebanon]]\n|formed=1991\n|deleted=2016\n|length_mi=77.28\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"840hold\"/>\n}}\n\nIn 1975 the Tennessee Highway System Plan issued by TDOT for the next four years first identified the need for an outer beltway around Nashville within the next 20 years.<ref name=FWHA>{{cite book |author = Tennessee Department of Transportation |year = 1995 |volume = Vol. 2 |title = Proposed Route 840 North from Interstate 65 to Interstate 40 West of Nashville in Robertson, Cheatham, Dickson, and Montgomery Counties, Tennessee |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=qrM1AQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false |location = Nashville |publisher = Tennessee Department of Transportation |page =  |id = FHWA-TN-ESI-9501-D |access-date = December 18, 2017 |via = Google Books }}</ref> The SR&nbsp;840 project was initiated in 1986 with the passage of the Better Roads Program in the [[Tennessee General Assembly]]. While initially referred to as I-840 in the state plan,<ref name=\"enjoytheride\"/> the highway was constructed entirely with state transportation funds and was officially referred to as a state route.<ref name=\"citypaper20121105\">{{cite news |first = Skip |last = Anderson |date = November 5, 2012 |url = http://www.nashvillecitypaper.com/content/city-news/state-route-840-opening-ends-arduous-laborious-and-costly-project |title = State Route&nbsp;840 Opening Ends Arduous, Laborious and Costly Project |work = [[The City Paper]] |location = Nashville |access-date = June 11, 2015 |url-status = dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130624131225/http://www.nashvillecitypaper.com/content/city-news/state-route-840-opening-ends-arduous-laborious-and-costly-project |archive-date = June 24, 2013 }}</ref> The 1986\u20131987 state budget contained the initial funding for the project.<ref name=\"enjoytheride\"/> The first contract for construction was signed in 1991, and work progressed in stages.<ref name=\"enjoytheride\"/>\n\nThe first section of SR 840 between I-40 in Lebanon and Stewart's Ferry Pike opened in August 1995.<ref name=\"840brief\">{{cite web |author = Tennessee Department of Transportation |date = n.d. |url = http://www.tdot.state.tn.us/sr840s/history.htm |title = SR&nbsp;840 South: Brief History |publisher = Tennessee Department of Transportation |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070714154129/http://www.tdot.state.tn.us/sr840s/history.htm |archive-date = July 14, 2007 }}</ref> The extension to I-24 near Murfreesboro was completed on November 21, 1996,<ref>{{cite press release |author = Tennessee Department of Transportation |title = Future I-840 Opens from Lebanon to Murfreesboro |url = http://www.state.tn.us/transport/oldpress/press04.htm |location = Nashville |publisher = Tennessee Department of Transportation |date = November 18, 1996 |access-date = March 31, 2020 |url-status = dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/19970723040442/http://www.state.tn.us/transport/oldpress/press04.htm |archive-date = July  23, 1997 }}</ref> and the section between I-24 and US 31 Alternate (US 31A) near [[Triune, Tennessee|Triune]] was completed on November 30, 2000.<ref>{{cite press release |author = Tennessee Department of Transportation |title = Twelve New Miles of State Route 840 Opens |url = http://www.tdot.state.tn.us/information-office/2000PressReleases/Nov2000.htm |location = Nashville |publisher = Tennessee Department of Transportation |date = November 28, 2000 |access-date = March 26, 2020 |url-status = dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20020619021712/http://www.tdot.state.tn.us/information-office/2000PressReleases/Nov2000.htm#026 |archive-date = June 19, 2002 }}</ref> The portion between US 31A and I-65 near Franklin opened on October 18, 2001.<ref>{{cite press release |author = Tennessee Department of Transportation |title = 840 Opens Connecting Lebanon, Murfreesboro and Franklin |url = http://www.tdot.state.tn.us/information-office/HotProjects/SR840/840open.htm |location = Nashville |publisher = Tennessee Department of Transportation |date = October 18, 2001 |access-date = March 26, 2020 |url-status = dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20020606025715/http://www.tdot.state.tn.us/information-office/HotProjects/SR840/840open.htm |archive-date = June 6, 2002 }}</ref> The section between I-40 near Dickson and SR&nbsp;100 opened on December 5, 2002.<ref name=\"enjoytheride\"/> Due to high costs and environmental concerns, the proposed northern half of SR&nbsp;840 was indefinitely placed on hold in 2003.<ref name=\"enjoytheride\"/> The western terminus was constructed in anticipation of the northern loop.<ref name=google/> As work moved into Williamson County, residents filed complaints and eventually lawsuits in an effort to have TDOT address both environmental and aesthetic issues, considerably slowing work in that county.<ref name=\"citypaper20121105\"/> As a result, TDOT chose to slightly modify the design and employ new construction methods.<ref name=\"enjoytheride\"/> The section between US 31 (Columbia Pike) and US 431 (Lewisburg Pike) opened to traffic on September 9, 2005.<ref>{{cite press release |url = http://www.tdot.state.tn.us/news/2005/090905.htm |title = New Section of State Route 840 Opens to Traffic |author = Tennessee Department of Transportation |date = September 9, 2005 |location = Nashville |publisher = Tennessee Department of Transportation |access-date = March 26, 2020 |url-status = dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20051227001155/http://www.tdot.state.tn.us/news/2005/090905.htm |archive-date = January 25, 2007 }}</ref> Work began on the segment between SR 100 and SR 46 in July 2007, and was opened on October 27, 2010.<ref>{{cite press release |first = Julie |last = Oaks |url = http://news.tn.gov/node/6253 |title = Governor Bredesen Opens New Section of State Route 840 |date = October 27, 2010 |location = Nashville |publisher = Tennessee Department of Transportation |access-date = April 12, 2019 |url-status = dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130416232012/http://news.tn.gov/node/6253 |archive-date = April 16, 2013 }}</ref> Work began on the segment between Leiper's Creek Road and US 31 in January 2009, and between SR 46 and Leiper's Creek Road in March 2010.<ref>{{cite news |last = Lovely |first = Lori |date = May 4, 2010 |title = Rounding Off SR 840 Circle Around Nashville |url = https://www.constructionequipmentguide.com/rounding-off-sr-840-circle-around-nashville/14362 |work = Construction Equipment Guide |location =  |access-date = April 12, 2019 }}</ref> These two segments, the final {{convert|12|mi|km}} of SR&nbsp;840, were opened on November 2, 2012.<ref name=\"enjoytheride\"/> The project took 26 years to complete at a cost of $753.4 million.<ref name=\"citypaper20121105\"/>\n\n===Northern loop===\n[[File:SR-840 former.png|thumb|right|Sign for SR 840 at western terminus on Interstate 40 in 2013.]]\nTDOT was first authorized to begin studies for a northern loop of I-840 north of Nashville and past Dickson, [[Clarksville, Tennessee|Clarksville]], [[Springfield, Tennessee|Springfield]], and [[Gallatin, Tennessee|Gallatin]] by the state legislature in 1993.<ref name=\"840hold\"/> Environmental studies began in 1994 and a [[draft environmental impact statement|draft]] [[environmental impact statement]] (DEIS) was released in 1995.<ref name=FWHA/> Many residents in the predominantly rural and agricultural areas where the route was to pass were initially opposed.<ref name=FWHA/> Plans were later abandoned and the General Assembly ordered TDOT to discontinue further studies and planning of that highway because of state budget problems. An entire circular loop would possibly be about {{convert|178|mi|km}} long, ranging from {{convert|86|to|116|mi|km}}. Other important objections against additional extensions of the I-840 highway include the hilly nature of the terrain north of Nashville (the [[Highland Rim]]), which would require huge and costly amounts of excavation, soil relocation, and bridge construction. In October 2003, TDOT placed the northern loop plan on indefinite hold, citing a lack of documented transportation needs and lack of participation from local politicians.<ref name=\"840hold\">{{cite press release |author = [[Tennessee Department of Transportation]] |date = October 31, 2003 |url = http://www.tdot.state.tn.us/news/2003/ut_projects/10-31-2003sr840n.pdf |title = TDOT Announces Decision on State Route 840 North |publisher = Tennessee Department of Transportation |format = PDF |access-date = July 17, 2007 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071127233215/http://www.tdot.state.tn.us/news/2003/ut_projects/10-31-2003sr840n.pdf |archive-date = November 27, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n===Redesignation===\n[[File:Interstate 840.jpg|thumb|right|Same section of I-40 in 2017, showing signage for I-840.]]\nIn 2015, TDOT submitted a request to [[American Association of State Highway and Transportation Officials|AASHTO]] to redesignate SR&nbsp;840 as I-840.  Though the application had an error that required TDOT to refile it, AASHTO conditionally approved it and submitted it to the [[Federal Highway Administration|FHWA]] for their approval.<ref>{{AASHTO minutes |year = 2015S |page = 6 |link = yes |access-date =June 6, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite letter |last = Wright |first = Bud |date = June 4, 2015 |url = http://route.transportation.org/Documents/05%2014%202015%20Cheyenne%2c%20WY%20Report/AASHTO%20to%20FHWA%20on%20Interstate%20Applications%20for%20I-840%20TN.pdf |title = Interstate Applications for I-840 TN |recipient = Greg Nadeau |location = Washington, DC |publisher = American Association of State Highway and Transportation Officials |access-date = June 6, 2015 }}</ref> FHWA approved the change on July 22, 2015, and AASHTO finalized their approval on September 25, 2015.<ref>{{AASHTO minutes |year = 2015A |page = 1 |access-date = December 18, 2015 }}</ref> TDOT announced that it would start replacing the signs to change over the designation the week of August 14, 2016, and that the project would be completed by the end of the year at a cost of $230,000.<ref name=\"tdot20160812\">{{cite press release |author = Tennessee Department of Transportation |date = August 12, 2016 |url = https://www.tn.gov/tdot/news/44772 |title = Tennessee Adds New 77 Miles of Highway to Interstate System: State Route 840 Now Designated as Interstate 840 |location = Nashville |publisher = Tennessee Department of Transportation |access-date = August 12, 2016 }}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Exit list==\n{{Jcttop|exit|length_ref=<ref name=gm/>}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|county=Dickson\n|location=none\n|mile=0.0\n|exit=1\n|road={{jct|state=TN|I|40|city1=Nashville|city2=Memphis}}\n|notes=Signed as exits 1A (west) and 1B (east) westbound; I-40 exit 176; [[stub road]] westbound}}\n{{jctco|state=TN|county=Hickman}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|county=Williamson\n|cspan=9\n|location=none\n|lspan=2\n|mile=7.3\n|exit=7\n|road={{jct|state=TN|TN|100|Sec|46|city1=Fairview|city2=Centerville}}\n|notes=}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|mile=14.1\n|exit=14\n|road={{jct|state=TN|Sec|46|name1=Pinewood Road|city1=Leiper's Fork}}\n|notes=}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|location=Burwood\n|mile=22.9\n|exit=23\n|road={{jct|state=TN|Sec|246|name1=Carters Creek Pike}}\n|notes=}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|location=Thompson's Station\n|lspan=3\n|mile=28.3\n|exit=28\n|road={{jct|state=TN|US|31|name1=Columbia Pike/[[Tennessee State Route 6|SR 6]]|city1=Columbia|city2=Spring Hill|city3=Franklin}}\n|notes=}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|mile=30.3\n|exit=30\n|road={{jct|state=TN|US|431|name1=Lewisburg Pike/[[Tennessee State Route 106|SR 106]]|city1=Franklin|city2=Lewisburg}}\n|notes=}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|exit=31\n|mile=31.1\n|road={{jct|state=TN|I|65|city1=Nashville|location2=[[Huntsville, Alabama|Huntsville, AL]]}}\n|notes=Signed as exits 31A (south) and 31B (north); I-65 exit 59 }}\n{{TNint|exit\n|location=Peytonsville\n|mile=34.9\n|exit=34\n|road=Peytonsville\u2013Trinity Road\n|notes=}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|location=none\n|mile=37.1\n|exit=37\n|road=Arno Road\n|notes=}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|location=Triune\n|mile=41.9\n|exit=42\n|road={{jct|state=TN|US|31A|US|41A|name2=Horton Highway/[[Tennessee State Route 11|SR 11]]|city1=Shelbyville|city2=Lewisburg|city3=Nolensville}}\n|notes=}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|county=Rutherford\n|cspan=7\n|location=Almaville\n|mile=46.9\n|exit=47\n|road={{jct|state=TN|Sec|102|name1=Almaville Road|city1=Smyrna}}\n|notes=}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|location=Blackman\n|mile=50.8\n|exit=50\n|road=Veterans Parkway&nbsp;\u2013 [[Blackman, Tennessee|Blackman]]\n|notes=}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|location=Murfreesboro\n|lspan=2\n|mile=53.1\n|exit=53\n|road={{jct|state=TN|I|24|city1=Nashville|city2=Chattanooga}}\n|notes=Signed as exits 53A (east) and 53B (west) westbound; I-24 exit 74}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|mile=55.1\n|exit=55\n|road={{jct|state=TN|US|41|US|70S|name2=NW Broad Street/New Nashville Highway/[[Tennessee State Route 1|SR 1]]|city1=Murfreesboro|city2=Smyrna}}\n|notes=Signed as exits 55A (south/east) and 55B (north/west)}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|location=none\n|lspan=3\n|mile=57.8\n|exit=57\n|road=Sulphur Springs Road\n|notes=}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|mile=61.4\n|exit=61\n|road={{jct|state=TN|Sec|266|name1=West Jefferson Pike|city1=Smyrna}}\n|notes=}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|mile=65.2\n|exit=65\n|road={{jct|state=TN|TN|452|name1=Bill France Boulevard|location1=[[Nashville Superspeedway]]}}\n|notes=}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|county=Wilson\n|cspan=4\n|location=none\n|mile=67.2\n|exit=67\n|road=Couchville Pike\n|notes=Exit to [[Cedars of Lebanon State Park]]}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|location=Gladeville\n|mile=70.6\n|exit=70\n|road=Stewarts Ferry Pike&nbsp;\u2013 [[Gladeville, Tennessee|Gladeville]]\n|notes=}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|location=none\n|mile=72.0\n|exit=72\n|road={{jct|state=TN|Sec|265|TN|109|dir2=north|to2=yes|name1=Central Pike}}\n|notes=Signed as 72A (east) and 72B (west) eastbound}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|location=Lebanon\n|mile=76.8\n|exit=76\n|road={{jct|state=TN|I|40|city1=Nashville|city2=Knoxville|city3=Lebanon}}\n|notes=Signed as exits 76A (east) and left 76B (west); I-40 exit 235;}}\n{{Jctbtm|exit}}\n\n==See also==\n*{{Portal-inline|U.S. Roads}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Interstate 840 (Tennessee)}}\n{{Attached KML|display=inline,title}}\n*[http://www.kurumi.com/roads/3di/i840.html Interstate 840] at Kurumi.com\n*[http://www.interstate-guide.com/i-840_tn.html Interstate 840] at Interstate-Guide.com\n\n{{3di|40}}\n\n[[Category:Interstate Highways in Tennessee|40-8]]\n[[Category:Beltways in the United States|840]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Dickson County, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Hickman County, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Williamson County, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Rutherford County, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Wilson County, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Auxiliary Interstate Highways|40-8 Tennessee]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Highway in Tennessee}}\n{{Infobox road\n|state=TN\n|type=I\n|route=840\n|alternate_name= Tennessee National Guard Parkway\n|map={{maplink|frame=yes|plain=yes|frame-align=center|frame-width=290|frame-height=250|frame-lat=35.998|frame-long=-86.808|zoom=8|type=line|raw={{Wikipedia:Map data/Wikipedia KML/Interstate 840 (Tennessee)}}}}\n|map_custom=yes\n|map_notes=I-840 highlighted in red\n|length_mi=77.28\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"840hold\"/>\n|established=August 12, 2016\n|spur_type=I\n|spur_of=40\n|direction_a=West\n|terminus_a={{jct|state=TN|I|40}} near [[Dickson, Tennessee|Dickson]]\n|junction={{plainlist|1=\n*{{jct|state=TN|I|65}} near [[Franklin, Tennessee|Franklin]]\n*{{jct|state=TN|I|24}} near [[Murfreesboro, Tennessee|Murfreesboro]] }}\n|direction_b=East\n|terminus_b={{jct|state=TN|I|40}} near [[Lebanon, Tennessee|Lebanon]]\n|counties=[[Dickson County, Tennessee|Dickson]], [[Hickman County, Tennessee|Hickman]], [[Williamson County, Tennessee|Williamson]], [[Rutherford County, Tennessee|Rutherford]], [[Wilson County, Tennessee|Wilson]]\n|previous_type=US\n|previous_route=641\n|next_type=SR\n|next_route=1\n}}\n'''Interstate 840''' ('''I-840'''), formerly '''State Route 840''' ('''SR&nbsp;840'''), also designated as '''Tennessee National Guard Parkway''',<ref name=\"enjoytheride\">{{cite book |author = Tennessee Department of Transportation |year = 2012 |url = http://www.tdot.state.tn.us/sr840s/docs/840book11-1.pdf |title = State Route&nbsp;840: Enjoy the Ride |type = Dedication program |publisher = Tennessee Department of Transportation |access-date = June 12, 2015 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121119032423/http://www.tdot.state.tn.us/sr840s/docs/840book11-1.pdf |archive-date = November 19, 2012 }}</ref> is a loop interstate highway around [[Nashville, Tennessee]], built by the [[Tennessee Department of Transportation]] (TDOT). First proposed by former Governor [[Lamar Alexander]] as part of a system of Bicentennial Parkways, construction began in 1991 and was completed in 2012. The [[freeway]] is {{convert|77.28|mi|km}} long,<ref name=\"840hold\"/> and it serves the cities of [[Lebanon, Tennessee|Lebanon]], [[Murfreesboro, Tennessee|Murfreesboro]], [[Franklin, Tennessee|Franklin]], and [[Dickson, Tennessee|Dickson]].<ref name=TDOT>{{cite map |author = Tennessee Department of Transportation |year = 2014 |title = Tennessee: 2014 Official Transportation Map |scale = c. 1:633,600 |location = Nashville |publisher = Tennessee Department of Transportation |sections = C7\u2013B8 }}</ref><ref name=gm>{{google maps |url = https://www.google.com/maps/dir/36.0215803,-87.2653359/36.1836542,-86.3521029/@35.993783,-86.78102,11z/data=!4m9!4m8!1m5!3m4!1m2!1d-86.7223008!2d35.8338299!3s0x88638866c916df7d:0x63cd9e63c74868ca!1m0!3e0 |title = State Route&nbsp;840 |access-date = June 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, approval was given by the [[Federal Highway Administration]] (FHWA) and the [[American Association of State Highway and Transportation Officials]] (AASHTO) to redesignate SR&nbsp;840 as Interstate&nbsp;840 (I-840) as part of its integration into the [[Interstate Highway System]]. On August 12, 2016, TDOT announced that it would begin re-signing the route on August 14 and that work would be complete later in the year.\n\n==Route description==\nI-840 begins at an interchange in [[Dickson County, Tennessee|Dickson County]] near Dickson. It initially runs southeast through a predominantly hilly terrain, and comes to an interchange with [[Tennessee State Route 100|State Route 100]] (SR 100) about {{convert|7.3|mi|km}} later. About ten miles later it crosses the [[Natchez Trace Parkway]] and turns east. I-840 has an interchange with [[U.S. Route 31 in Tennessee|U.S. Route 31]] (US 31) about ten miles later, and about {{convert|3|mi|km}} later comes to an interchange with [[Interstate 65 in Tennessee|I-65]] south of Franklin in an interchange that resembles a [[cloverstack interchange]], containing two loop ramps and two underpass ramps that cross I-840 combined together. The route continues through a hilly terrain with several steep grades, and comes to an interchange with [[U.S. Route 31 Alternate (Tennessee)|US 31 Alternate]] and [[U.S. Route 41 Alternate (Monteagle, Tennessee \u2013 Hopkinsville, Kentucky)|41 Alternate]] about {{convert|11|mi|km}} later. About {{convert|3|mi|km}} later I-840 crosses [[Tennessee State Route 96|State Route 96]] (SR 96), and about {{convert|9|mi|km}} later comes to an interchange with I-24 southwest of [[Murfreesboro, Tennessee|Murfreesboro]]. This interchange is almost a complete [[cloverleaf interchange|cloverleaf]], containing three loop ramps and one [[overpass|flyover]]. The route turns northeast, passing through a predominantly rural and agricultural area, and about {{convert|19|mi|km}} later comes to an interchange with [[Tennessee State Route 109|State Route 109]] (SR 109). The route turns slightly northeast, and about {{convert|3.8|mi|km}} later reaches its eastern terminus with I-40 in [[Wilson County, Tennessee|Wilson County]] west of Lebanon.<ref name=google>{{google maps |url = https://www.google.com/maps/place/I-840,+Tennessee/@36.0861572,-86.596612,66351m/data=!3m1!1e3!4m5!3m4!1s0x88647b9afed8536b:0x963e9004ea8fed0f!8m2!3d36.0895955!4d-86.427016 |title = I-840 |access-date = December 18, 2017 |link = no }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{Infobox road small\n|state=TN\n|type=SR\n|route=840\n|location=[[Dickson, Tennessee|Dickson]]\u2013[[Lebanon, Tennessee|Lebanon]]\n|formed=1991\n|deleted=2016\n|length_mi=77.28\n|length_ref=<ref name=\"840hold\"/>\n}}\n\nIn 1975 the Tennessee Highway System Plan issued by TDOT for the next four years first identified the need for an outer beltway around Nashville within the next 20 years.<ref name=FWHA>{{cite book |author = Tennessee Department of Transportation |year = 1995 |volume = Vol. 2 |title = Proposed Route 840 North from Interstate 65 to Interstate 40 West of Nashville in Robertson, Cheatham, Dickson, and Montgomery Counties, Tennessee |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=qrM1AQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false |location = Nashville |publisher = Tennessee Department of Transportation |page =  |id = FHWA-TN-ESI-9501-D |access-date = December 18, 2017 |via = Google Books }}</ref> The SR&nbsp;840 project was initiated in 1986 with the passage of the Better Roads Program in the [[Tennessee General Assembly]]. While initially referred to as I-840 in the state plan,<ref name=\"enjoytheride\"/> the highway was constructed entirely with state transportation funds and was officially referred to as a state route.<ref name=\"citypaper20121105\">{{cite news |first = Skip |last = Anderson |date = November 5, 2012 |url = http://www.nashvillecitypaper.com/content/city-news/state-route-840-opening-ends-arduous-laborious-and-costly-project |title = State Route&nbsp;840 Opening Ends Arduous, Laborious and Costly Project |work = [[The City Paper]] |location = Nashville |access-date = June 11, 2015 |url-status = dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130624131225/http://www.nashvillecitypaper.com/content/city-news/state-route-840-opening-ends-arduous-laborious-and-costly-project |archive-date = June 24, 2013 }}</ref> The 1986\u20131987 state budget contained the initial funding for the project.<ref name=\"enjoytheride\"/> The first contract for construction was signed in 1991, and work progressed in stages.<ref name=\"enjoytheride\"/>\n\nThe first section of SR 840 between I-40 in Lebanon and Stewart's Ferry Pike opened in August 1995.<ref name=\"840brief\">{{cite web |author = Tennessee Department of Transportation |date = n.d. |url = http://www.tdot.state.tn.us/sr840s/history.htm |title = SR&nbsp;840 South: Brief History |publisher = Tennessee Department of Transportation |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070714154129/http://www.tdot.state.tn.us/sr840s/history.htm |archive-date = July 14, 2007 }}</ref> The extension to I-24 near Murfreesboro was completed on November 21, 1996,<ref>{{cite press release |author = Tennessee Department of Transportation |title = Future I-840 Opens from Lebanon to Murfreesboro |url = http://www.state.tn.us/transport/oldpress/press04.htm |location = Nashville |publisher = Tennessee Department of Transportation |date = November 18, 1996 |access-date = March 31, 2020 |url-status = dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/19970723040442/http://www.state.tn.us/transport/oldpress/press04.htm |archive-date = July  23, 1997 }}</ref> and the section between I-24 and US 31 Alternate (US 31A) near [[Triune, Tennessee|Triune]] was completed on November 30, 2000.<ref>{{cite press release |author = Tennessee Department of Transportation |title = Twelve New Miles of State Route 840 Opens |url = http://www.tdot.state.tn.us/information-office/2000PressReleases/Nov2000.htm |location = Nashville |publisher = Tennessee Department of Transportation |date = November 28, 2000 |access-date = March 26, 2020 |url-status = dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20020619021712/http://www.tdot.state.tn.us/information-office/2000PressReleases/Nov2000.htm#026 |archive-date = June 19, 2002 }}</ref> The portion between US 31A and I-65 near Franklin opened on October 18, 2001.<ref>{{cite press release |author = Tennessee Department of Transportation |title = 840 Opens Connecting Lebanon, Murfreesboro and Franklin |url = http://www.tdot.state.tn.us/information-office/HotProjects/SR840/840open.htm |location = Nashville |publisher = Tennessee Department of Transportation |date = October 18, 2001 |access-date = March 26, 2020 |url-status = dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20020606025715/http://www.tdot.state.tn.us/information-office/HotProjects/SR840/840open.htm |archive-date = June 6, 2002 }}</ref> The section between I-40 near Dickson and SR&nbsp;100 opened on December 5, 2002.<ref name=\"enjoytheride\"/> Due to high costs and environmental concerns, the proposed northern half of SR&nbsp;840 was indefinitely placed on hold in 2003.<ref name=\"enjoytheride\"/> The western terminus was constructed in anticipation of the northern loop.<ref name=google/> As work moved into Williamson County, residents filed complaints and eventually lawsuits in an effort to have TDOT address both environmental and aesthetic issues, considerably slowing work in that county.<ref name=\"citypaper20121105\"/> As a result, TDOT chose to slightly modify the design and employ new construction methods.<ref name=\"enjoytheride\"/> The section between US 31 (Columbia Pike) and US 431 (Lewisburg Pike) opened to traffic on September 9, 2005.<ref>{{cite press release |url = http://www.tdot.state.tn.us/news/2005/090905.htm |title = New Section of State Route 840 Opens to Traffic |author = Tennessee Department of Transportation |date = September 9, 2005 |location = Nashville |publisher = Tennessee Department of Transportation |access-date = March 26, 2020 |url-status = dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20051227001155/http://www.tdot.state.tn.us/news/2005/090905.htm |archive-date = January 25, 2007 }}</ref> Work began on the segment between SR 100 and SR 46 in July 2007, and was opened on October 27, 2010.<ref>{{cite press release |first = Julie |last = Oaks |url = http://news.tn.gov/node/6253 |title = Governor Bredesen Opens New Section of State Route 840 |date = October 27, 2010 |location = Nashville |publisher = Tennessee Department of Transportation |access-date = April 12, 2019 |url-status = dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130416232012/http://news.tn.gov/node/6253 |archive-date = April 16, 2013 }}</ref> Work began on the segment between Leiper's Creek Road and US 31 in January 2009, and between SR 46 and Leiper's Creek Road in March 2010.<ref>{{cite news |last = Lovely |first = Lori |date = May 4, 2010 |title = Rounding Off SR 840 Circle Around Nashville |url = https://www.constructionequipmentguide.com/rounding-off-sr-840-circle-around-nashville/14362 |work = Construction Equipment Guide |location =  |access-date = April 12, 2019 }}</ref> These two segments, the final {{convert|12|mi|km}} of SR&nbsp;840, were opened on November 2, 2012.<ref name=\"enjoytheride\"/> The project took 26 years to complete at a cost of $753.4 million.<ref name=\"citypaper20121105\"/>\n\n===Northern loop===\n[[File:SR-840 former.png|thumb|right|Sign for SR 840 at western terminus on Interstate 40 in 2013.]]\nTDOT was first authorized to begin studies for a northern loop of I-840 north of Nashville and past Dickson, [[Clarksville, Tennessee|Clarksville]], [[Springfield, Tennessee|Springfield]], and [[Gallatin, Tennessee|Gallatin]] by the state legislature in 1993.<ref name=\"840hold\"/> Environmental studies began in 1994 and a [[draft environmental impact statement|draft]] [[environmental impact statement]] (DEIS) was released in 1995.<ref name=FWHA/> Many residents in the predominantly rural and agricultural areas where the route was to pass were initially opposed.<ref name=FWHA/> Plans were later abandoned and the General Assembly ordered TDOT to discontinue further studies and planning of that highway because of state budget problems. An entire circular loop would possibly be about {{convert|178|mi|km}} long, ranging from {{convert|86|to|116|mi|km}}. Other important objections against additional extensions of the I-840 highway include the hilly nature of the terrain north of Nashville (the [[Highland Rim]]), which would require huge and costly amounts of excavation, soil relocation, and bridge construction. In October 2003, TDOT placed the northern loop plan on indefinite hold, citing a lack of documented transportation needs and lack of participation from local politicians.<ref name=\"840hold\">{{cite press release |author = [[Tennessee Department of Transportation]] |date = October 31, 2003 |url = http://www.tdot.state.tn.us/news/2003/ut_projects/10-31-2003sr840n.pdf |title = TDOT Announces Decision on State Route 840 North |publisher = Tennessee Department of Transportation |format = PDF |access-date = July 17, 2007 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071127233215/http://www.tdot.state.tn.us/news/2003/ut_projects/10-31-2003sr840n.pdf |archive-date = November 27, 2007 }}</ref>\n\n===Redesignation===\n[[File:Interstate 840.jpg|thumb|right|Same section of I-40 in 2017, showing signage for I-840.]]\nIn 2015, TDOT submitted a request to [[American Association of State Highway and Transportation Officials|AASHTO]] to redesignate SR&nbsp;840 as I-840.  Though the application had an error that required TDOT to refile it, AASHTO conditionally approved it and submitted it to the [[Federal Highway Administration|FHWA]] for their approval.<ref>{{AASHTO minutes |year = 2015S |page = 6 |link = yes |access-date =June 6, 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite letter |last = Wright |first = Bud |date = June 4, 2015 |url = http://route.transportation.org/Documents/05%2014%202015%20Cheyenne%2c%20WY%20Report/AASHTO%20to%20FHWA%20on%20Interstate%20Applications%20for%20I-840%20TN.pdf |title = Interstate Applications for I-840 TN |recipient = Greg Nadeau |location = Washington, DC |publisher = American Association of State Highway and Transportation Officials |access-date = June 6, 2015 }}</ref> FHWA approved the change on July 22, 2015, and AASHTO finalized their approval on September 25, 2015.<ref>{{AASHTO minutes |year = 2015A |page = 1 |access-date = December 18, 2015 }}</ref> TDOT announced that it would start replacing the signs to change over the designation the week of August 14, 2016, and that the project would be completed by the end of the year at a cost of $230,000.<ref name=\"tdot20160812\">{{cite press release |author = Tennessee Department of Transportation |date = August 12, 2016 |url = https://www.tn.gov/tdot/news/44772 |title = Tennessee Adds New 77 Miles of Highway to Interstate System: State Route 840 Now Designated as Interstate 840 |location = Nashville |publisher = Tennessee Department of Transportation |access-date = August 12, 2016 }}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Exit list==\n{{Jcttop|exit|length_ref=<ref name=gm/>}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|county=Dickson\n|location=none\n|mile=0.0\n|exit=1\n|road={{jct|state=TN|I|40|city1=Nashville|city2=Memphis}}\n|notes=Signed as exits 1A (west) and 1B (east) westbound; I-40 exit 176; [[stub road]] westbound}}\n{{jctco|state=TN|county=Hickman}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|county=Williamson\n|cspan=9\n|location=none\n|lspan=2\n|mile=7.3\n|exit=7\n|road={{jct|state=TN|TN|100|Sec|46|city1=Fairview|city2=Centerville}}\n|notes=}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|mile=14.1\n|exit=14\n|road={{jct|state=TN|Sec|46|name1=Pinewood Road|city1=Leiper's Fork}}\n|notes=}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|location=Burwood\n|mile=22.9\n|exit=23\n|road={{jct|state=TN|Sec|246|name1=Carters Creek Pike}}\n|notes=}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|location=Thompson's Station\n|lspan=3\n|mile=28.3\n|exit=28\n|road={{jct|state=TN|US|31|name1=Columbia Pike/[[Tennessee State Route 6|SR 6]]|city1=Columbia|city2=Spring Hill|city3=Franklin}}\n|notes=}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|mile=30.3\n|exit=30\n|road={{jct|state=TN|US|431|name1=Lewisburg Pike/[[Tennessee State Route 106|SR 106]]|city1=Franklin|city2=Lewisburg}}\n|notes=}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|exit=31\n|mile=31.1\n|road={{jct|state=TN|I|65|city1=Nashville|location2=[[Huntsville, Alabama|Huntsville, AL]]}}\n|notes=Signed as exits 31A (south) and 31B (north); I-65 exit 59 }}\n{{TNint|exit\n|location=Peytonsville\n|mile=34.9\n|exit=34\n|road=Peytonsville\u2013Trinity Road\n|notes=}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|location=none\n|mile=37.1\n|exit=37\n|road=Arno Road\n|notes=}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|location=Triune\n|mile=41.9\n|exit=42\n|road={{jct|state=TN|US|31A|US|41A|name2=Horton Highway/[[Tennessee State Route 11|SR 11]]|city1=Shelbyville|city2=Lewisburg|city3=Nolensville}}\n|notes=}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|county=Rutherford\n|cspan=7\n|location=Almaville\n|mile=46.9\n|exit=47\n|road={{jct|state=TN|Sec|102|name1=Almaville Road|city1=Smyrna}}\n|notes=}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|location=Blackman\n|mile=50.8\n|exit=50\n|road=Veterans Parkway&nbsp;\u2013 [[Blackman, Tennessee|Blackman]]\n|notes=}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|location=Murfreesboro\n|lspan=2\n|mile=53.1\n|exit=53\n|road={{jct|state=TN|I|24|city1=Nashville|city2=Chattanooga}}\n|notes=Signed as exits 53A (east) and 53B (west) westbound; I-24 exit 74}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|mile=55.1\n|exit=55\n|road={{jct|state=TN|US|41|US|70S|name2=NW Broad Street/New Nashville Highway/[[Tennessee State Route 1|SR 1]]|city1=Murfreesboro|city2=Smyrna}}\n|notes=Signed as exits 55A (south/east) and 55B (north/west)}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|location=none\n|lspan=3\n|mile=57.8\n|exit=57\n|road=Sulphur Springs Road\n|notes=}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|mile=61.4\n|exit=61\n|road={{jct|state=TN|Sec|266|name1=West Jefferson Pike|city1=Smyrna}}\n|notes=}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|mile=65.2\n|exit=65\n|road={{jct|state=TN|TN|452|name1=Bill France Boulevard|location1=[[Nashville Superspeedway]]}}\n|notes=}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|county=Wilson\n|cspan=4\n|location=none\n|mile=67.2\n|exit=67\n|road=Couchville Pike\n|notes=Exit to [[Cedars of Lebanon State Park]]}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|location=Gladeville\n|mile=70.6\n|exit=70\n|road=Stewarts Ferry Pike&nbsp;\u2013 [[Gladeville, Tennessee|Gladeville]]\n|notes=}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|location=none\n|mile=72.0\n|exit=72\n|road={{jct|state=TN|Sec|265|TN|109|dir2=north|to2=yes|name1=Central Pike}}\n|notes=Signed as 72A (east) and 72B (west) eastbound}}\n{{TNint|exit\n|location=Lebanon\n|mile=76.8\n|exit=76\n|road={{jct|state=TN|I|40|city1=Nashville|city2=Knoxville|city3=Lebanon}}\n|notes=Signed as exits 76A (east) and left 76B (west); I-40 exit 235;}}\n{{Jctbtm|exit}}\n\n==See also==\n*{{Portal-inline|U.S. Roads}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Interstate 840 (Tennessee)}}\n{{Attached KML|display=inline,title}}\n*[http://www.kurumi.com/roads/3di/i840.html Interstate 840] at Kurumi.com\n*[http://www.interstate-guide.com/i-840_tn.html Interstate 840] at Interstate-Guide.com\n\n{{3di|40}}\n\n[[Category:Interstate Highways in Tennessee|40-8]]\n[[Category:Beltways in the United States|840]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Dickson County, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Hickman County, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Williamson County, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Rutherford County, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Wilson County, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Auxiliary Interstate Highways|40-8 Tennessee]]\n", "name_user": "Bneu2013", "label": "safe", "comment": "describe in lead reason for SR designation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interstate_840_(Tennessee)"}
