 Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2018_Gazetteer/2018_gaz_place_49.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Feb 16, 2020}}</ref>\n| area_total_km2 = 17.30\n| area_land_km2 = 17.30\n| area_water_km2 = 0.00\n| area_total_sq_mi = 6.68\n| area_land_sq_mi = 6.68\n| area_water_sq_mi = 0.00\n| area_water_percent = \n \n| area_urban_km2 = \n \n| area_urban_sq_mi = \n \n| area_metro_km2 = \n \n| area_metro_sq_mi = \n \n| population_as_of = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n| population_footnotes = \n \n| population_note = \n \n| population_total = 3112\n| population_density_km2 = 179.39\n| opulation_density_sq_mi = \n \n| population_metro = \n \n| population_density_metro_km2 = \n \n| population_density_metro_sq_mi = \n \n| population_urban = \n \n| population_density_urban_km2 = \n \n| population_density_urban_sq_mi = \n \n| population_blank1_title = \n \n| population_blank1 = \n \n| population_density_blank1_km2 = \n \n| population_density_blank1_sq_mi = \n \n| timezone = [[Mountain Standard Time Zone|MST]]\n \n| utc_offset = -7\n \n| timezone_DST = [[Mountain Daylight Time|MDT]]\n \n| utc_offset_DST = -6\n \n| coordinates = {{coord|38|16|35|N|112|38|20|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n \n| elevation_footnotes = <ref name=usgs>{{gnis|1438510|Beaver}}</ref>\n \n| elevation_m = 1799\n \n| elevation_ft = 5902\n \n| postal_code_type = ZIP code\n \n| postal_code = 84713\n \n| area_code = 435\n \n| blank_name = [[Federal Information Processing Standards|FIPS code]]\n \n| blank_info = 49-04060<ref name=\"GR2\"/>\n \n| blank1_name = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n \n| blank1_info = 1438510<ref name=usgs/>\n \n| website = {{URL|www.beaverutah.net}}\n \n| footnotes = \n|pop_est_as_of = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018CenPopScriptOnlyDirtyFixDoNotUse\"/>\n|population_est = 3104\n|population_density_sq_mi = 464.60\n}}\n\n'''Beaver''' is a city in eastern [[Beaver County, Utah|Beaver County]], [[Utah]], [[United States]]. It also serves as the county seat. The population was 3,112 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]].<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/G001/1600000US4904060| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212203622/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/G001/1600000US4904060| url-status=dead| archive-date=February 12, 2020| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Demographic Profile Data (G001): Beaver city, Utah| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau, American Factfinder| accessdate=April 23, 2014}}</ref> It is the [[county seat]] of [[Beaver County, Utah|Beaver County]].<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web |url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |accessdate=2011-06-07 |title=Find a County |publisher=National Association of Counties |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120712220218/http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |archivedate=2012-07-12 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:MOUNT BALDY NEAR BEAVER, UTAH - NARA - 523958.jpg|thumb|left|210px|[[Bald Mountain (Uinta Range)|Mt. Baldy]] viewed from Beaver, photographed by [[William Bell (photographer)|William Bell]] during the 1872 [[Wheeler Survey]]]]\n\nIndigenous peoples lived in this area for thousands of years, as shown by archeological evidence. A number of identified prehistoric sites have been found in Beaver County, dating to the [[Archaic period in North America|Archaic]] and Sevier [[Fremont culture|Fremont]] periods. A prehistoric [[obsidian]] quarry site has been identified in the nearby [[Mineral Mountains (Utah)|Mineral Mountains]].\n\nThe historic [[Southern Paiute]] inhabited the region well before encounter with the first European explorers. The 1776 [[Dominguez\u2013Escalante Expedition]] is the first known European exploration in this area. {{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nIn 1847\u20131848, Mormons from the United States developed a trade route through the Beaver River valley between their new settlements at [[Salt Lake City]] in the Utah Territory and [[Los Angeles]], which was still part of [[Alta California]], [[Mexico]]. The original route crossed the river 3 miles downstream from Beaver at the site that later was developed as [[Greenville, Utah|Greenville]]. This route became known during the [[California Gold Rush]] as the Southern Route of the [[California Trail]]. Later called the [[Mormon Road]] or California Road, it passed over the [[Black Mountains (Utah)|Black Mountains]] between the crossing and [[Muley Point (Iron County, Utah)|Muley Point]]. Following United States victory in the [[Mexican\u2013American War]] (1846\u20131848), it took over California and the Southwest.\n\nIn 1855, as part of improvements, the Mormon Road over the Black Mountains was realigned eastward. It was routed from the site that developed as Beaver to [[Muley Point (Iron County, Utah)|Muley Point]] through more wagon-friendly terrain in [[Nevershine Hollow]] and over [[Beaver Ridge (Beaver County, Utah)|Beaver Ridge]] into the canyon of [[Fremont Wash]], rejoining the original road above Muley Point.  This road became a winter commercial wagon road, known in California as the Los Angeles \u2013 Salt Lake Road, and in Mormon settlements in [[Utah Territory|Utah]] and [[Arizona Territory]] (now southern Nevada) as the California Road.\n\nBeaver was settled in 1856 by [[Mormon pioneers]] traveling this road; it was one of a string of Mormon settlements along the road through Utah. By design, these settlements were located a day's ride on horseback apart, which explains the regularity of their spacing. They were generally {{convert|30|mi}} apart. Where intervening settlements failed or were absorbed, they became {{convert|60|mi}} apart. Beaver was developed between the settlements in the [[Pahvant Valley]] and those in the [[Parowan Valley]].\n\nIn 1873 the US Army established [[Fort Cameron]] two miles from Beaver because of Indian raids on the area Mormon settlements. To serve this isolated area, the territorial government placed the Second Judicial Court of the Utah Territory in Beaver from 1870 until 1896, when Utah became a state. Also included in this court's jurisdiction were Iron, [[Washington County, Utah|Washington]], [[Kane County, Utah|Kane]], [[Garfield County, Utah|Garfield]], and [[Piute County, Utah|Piute]] counties. {{citation needed|date=April 2015}}\n\nIn 1856 Mormons migrated to the [[Beaver Valley (Utah)|Beaver Valley]] from [[Parowan, Utah|Parowan]] to the south. George A. Smith called a council meeting in February 1856, and the men elected Simeon F. Howd as presiding elder and Edward W. Thompson, clerk. In 1858, numerous migrants from [[San Bernardino, California]], settled here.<ref>''Sketches from Life and Labors of Wilson Gates Nowers'' by Reinhard Maeser, PD.B.B.D Beaver City, Utah, 1914.</ref>  In December 1859, W. W. Willis and P. K. Smith were authorized by the council to build a sawmill and gristmill on North Creek, and given control of all water on the mill site.<ref>''A History of Beaver County,'' Martha Sonntag Bradley, Utah Centennial County History Series.</ref> By 1869, the Mormon settlers in Beaver were numerous enough to organize a [[stake (Latter Day Saints)|stake]]. The first stake president was [[John R. Murdock (Mormon)|John Murdock]].<ref>Jenson, Andrew. ''Encyclopedic History of The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints''. (Salt Lake City: Deseret News Press, 1941) p. 53</ref>\n\nDuring the 1870s, settlers made an effort to establish a woolen mill, a tannery, and a dairy industry. {{citation needed|date=April 2015}} Most were engaged in stock raising.\n\nBeaver was the first town in Utah to be [[electrified]]. A [[hydroelectric]] generation plant was constructed on the [[Beaver River (Utah)|Beaver River]] early in the 20th century. The plant continues to provide a large part of Beaver's power requirements today.\n\nIn 2006, Beaver won a contest for best tasting rural water in the United States.<ref name=water>{{cite news |author=[[Lee Benson]] |title=Beaver's water is worth a stop |newspaper=[[Deseret News]] |date=November 18, 2009 |url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/705345308/Beavers-water-is-worth-a-stop.html |accessdate=November 3, 2011}}</ref> In 2010, Beaver took top honors in the world for best tasting water.<ref name=bestwater>{{cite news|title=Utah water dubbed 'world's best'|newspaper=[[Salt Lake Tribune]] |date=April 21, 2010 |url=http://archive.sltrib.com/story.php?ref=/news/ci_14927314}}</ref> Its welcome billboards along I-15 highlight the water quality.\n\n==Notable natives and residents==\n<!-- Put and keep in alphabetical order by surname -->\n* [[Butch Cassidy]], born here, became a notorious outlaw in the American West\n* [[Philo T. Farnsworth]], inventor of several critical electronic devices that made television possible, including the [[image dissector]] tube. He was the first to create table-top nuclear fusion<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.americanscientist.org/issues/pub/fusion-from-television |title=Table-top nuclear fusion |access-date=2010-01-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090408030609/http://www.americanscientist.org/issues/pub/fusion-from-television |archive-date=2009-04-08 |url-status = dead}}</ref>{{Citation needed|date=May 2019}} and [[fusor]].\n*Richard LaVon Griffiths, also known as \"The Beaver Kid\" and \"Groovin' Gary,\" graduated from Beaver High School and worked in Beaver for most of his life. He is best known as the eccentric, honest, and charming subject of the cult-film ''[[The Beaver Trilogy]].''<ref name=\"fulton\">{{cite news |author= [[Ben Fulton]] |title = Utah's 'Beaver Kid' dies | newspaper = [[The Salt Lake Tribune]] | date =February 4, 2009 | url = http://archive.sltrib.com/story.php?ref=/news/ci_11628966 | accessdate = March 9, 2016}}</ref>\n*Brandon H.Lee, business strategy professor at the University of Melbourne.\n\n==Geography==\nBeaver is located in eastern Beaver County, along [[Interstate 15]], the main artery for the state of Utah. To the east of Beaver lie the [[Tushar Mountains]]. The peaks in these mountains rise to over {{convert|12000|ft|abbr=on}}. The [[Beaver River (Utah)|Beaver River]] flows out of the mountains and through the city of Beaver, passing south of downtown before continuing west towards [[Minersville, Utah|Minersville]] and the [[Escalante Desert]] basin. The [[Mineral Mountains (Utah)|Mineral Mountains]] rise to the west of Beaver, and the South Hills are to the south.\n\nInterstate 15 runs along the western edge of Beaver, with access from exits 109 and 112. I-15 leads north {{convert|22|mi|abbr=on}} to the western end of [[Interstate 70]] at [[Cove Fort]], {{convert|55|mi|abbr=on}} north to [[Fillmore, Utah|Fillmore]], and {{convert|53|mi|abbr=on}} south to [[Cedar City, Utah|Cedar City]]. [[Utah State Route 153]] heads east from Beaver across the Tushar Mountains {{convert|40|mi|abbr=on}} to [[Junction, Utah|Junction]], and [[Utah State Route 21]] runs west through the Beaver River Valley {{convert|17|mi|abbr=on}} to Minersville.\n\nThe [[American Discovery Trail]] runs through Beaver.<ref>https://discoverytrail.org/states/utah/ut-trail/</ref>\n\nAn important Beaver landmark is the [[hillside letter]] '''B''', which is visible from the freeway ({{coord|38|15|52.26|N|112|34|57.2|W|type:landmark_region:US|name=B for Beaver}}).\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the city has a total area of {{convert|16.8|km2|disp=flip|abbr=on}}, all of it land.<ref name=\"Census 2010\"/>\n\n===Climate===\nBeaver has a typical Intermountain Region [[semi-arid climate#Cold semi-arid climates|cool semi-arid climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification|K\u00f6ppen]] ''BSk''), bordering on a [[humid continental climate]] (''Dfb''), with summers characterized by hot days and chilly nights, and cold winters with moderate snowfall.\n\nDuring the summer, days are hot and usually dry, though on occasions, as in July 1936 \u2013 the wettest month on record with {{convert|5.76|in|mm|1|disp=or}} \u2013 [[North American Monsoon|monsoonal]] weather can bring heavy thunderstorms from the Gulf of California. Owing to the absence of cloudiness caused by the Great Salt Lake, nights are much cooler than in Salt Lake City or Ogden during this season. The hottest recorded temperature in Beaver is {{convert|102|F|C|1|disp=or}}, which has occurred twice on June 21, 1913 and July 26, 1931, and 23.3 days will on average top {{convert|90|F|C|1|disp=or}}, although the hottest monthly mean minimum is only {{convert|62.0|F|C|disp=or}} in July 1968.\n\nWinters are cold, though not severe, and generally dry, with the city's intermountain valley location making it sufficiently dry that only {{convert|34.1|in|m|2|disp=or}} of snowfall can be expected each winter. Typically temperatures fall below freezing on all but six nights during winter and on 193.7 nights during an entire year; however maxima will top freezing on all but 14.3 afternoons. Temperatures below {{convert|0|F|C|1|disp=or}} occur on 9.8 nights per winter, and the coldest temperature on record is {{convert|&minus;34|F|C|1|disp=or}} on February 9, 1933 during an exceptionally cold western winter. The most snowfall has been at least {{convert|80.50|in|m}} between July 1948 and June 1949, and the most in a month {{convert|33.5|in|m|2}} during the notoriously cold January 1949 which averaged a record low {{convert|9.9|F|C|disp=or}} with mean minimum as low as {{convert|&minus;2.1|F|C|disp=or}}; by way of contrast, no measurable snow fell during the mild, dry winter of 1962\u201363. The wettest calendar year has been 1936 with {{convert|20.78|in|mm|1}} and the driest 1956 with {{convert|5.82|in|mm|1}}; the most in one day being {{convert|2.17|in|mm|1}} on September 20, 1911.\n{{Weather box \n|location = Beaver, Utah (1889 to 1990)\n|single line = Y\n|Jan record high F = 